{"title_page": "Pirelli", "text_new": "{{coord|45.5195317|9.2111299|display=title}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Pirelli & C. [[Societ\u00e0 per azioni|S.p.A.]]\n| logo = Logo Pirelli.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| image = Pirelli headquarters.jpg \n| image_size = 250px\n| image_caption = Pirelli headquarters as seen in 2004\n| type = [[Societ\u00e0 per azioni]]\n| traded_as = {{BIT|IT0005278236|PIRC}}\n| ISIN = IT0005278236\n| founder = Giovanni Battista Pirelli\n| hq_location_city = Milan\n| hq_location_country =  Italy\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = [[Ning Gaoning]] ([[Chairman]])<br />[[Marco Tronchetti Provera]] ([[Chairman|Executive Vice Chairman]] and [[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]])\n| industry = [[Automotive]]\n| products = [[Tyres]] for [[car]], [[motorcycle]]s and [[cycling]]\n| revenue = \u20ac5.195 billion <small>(2018)</small><ref name=\"Highlights\">{{Cite web|url=https://corporate.pirelli.com/corporate/en-ww/investors/annual-report-2018|work=Pirelli|title=Highlights|language=en}}</ref>\n| operating_income = \u20ac703 million <small>(2018)</small><ref name=\"Highlights\" />\n| net_income = \u20ac442 million <small>(2018)</small><ref name=\"Highlights\" />\n| assets = \n| equity = \n| num_employees = 31,489 <small>(2018)</small>\n| subsid = Pirelli Tyre S.p.A.\n| foundation = {{start date and age|1872|df=yes}}<br>[[Milan]], [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]]\n| homepage = [http://www.pirelli.com pirelli.com]\n| parent = \n| owner = [[ChemChina]] (45.5%)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pirelli-ipo/chemchina-gave-up-pirelli-control-to-show-its-market-friendly-face-pirelli-ceo-idUSKCN1BT0YB|title=ChemChina gave up Pirelli control to show its market friendly face: Pirelli CEO|work=Reuters|author=Agnieszka Flak|author2=Elisa Anzolin|accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref><br>[[Marco Tronchetti Provera]] (10.05%)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/pirelli-ipo/pirelli-ceo-says-core-shareholders-have-no-plans-to-sell-stakes-idUSI6N1D100W|title=Pirelli CEO says core shareholders have no plans to sell stakes|work=Reuters|accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Pirelli & C. S.p.A.''' is an Italian [[multinational company]] based in [[Milan]], [[Italy]], listed on the [[Milan Stock Exchange]] since 1922,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.borsaitaliana.it/companyprofile/en/214.pdf|title=Pirelli Company Profile|publisher=Borsa Italiana|accessdate=21 February 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301192412/http://www.borsaitaliana.it/companyprofile/en/214.pdf|archivedate=1 March 2014}}</ref> with a temporary privatization period by the consortium led by the Chinese state-owned enterprise [[ChemChina]]. The company is the 5th<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tyrepress.com/leading-tyre-manufacturers/|title=Leading tyre manufacturers|date=2013-09-26|work=Tyrepress|access-date=2018-07-17|language=en-GB}}</ref> largest [[tire]] manufacturer behind [[Bridgestone]], [[Michelin]],  [[Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company|Goodyear]] and [[Continental AG|Continental]], and is focused on the consumer business (tires for cars, motorcycles and bicycles). It is present in [[Europe]], [[Asia-Pacific|the Asia-Pacific]], [[Latin America]], [[North American Free Trade Agreement|North America]] and ex-USSR, operating commercially in over 160 countries. It has 19 manufacturing sites<ref>{{cite web|url=http://corporate.pirelli.com/corporate/en-ww/aboutus/about-us|title=Pirelli \u2013 About us|last=|first=|date=|website=}}</ref> in 13 countries and a network of around 14,600 distributors and retailers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/psi-dotcom-prd/corporate/3149_2018.05.14_Company_Presentation+v15_LINKS.pdf|title=Pirelli Company Presentation|publisher=Pirelli|accessdate=18 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nPirelli has been sponsoring sport competitions since 1907 and is the exclusive tire supplier for the [[Grand-Am]] [[Rolex Sports Car Series]] for 2008\u20132010, [[FIA Formula One World Championship]] for 2011\u20132023<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/pirelli-tyre-supply-deal-2023/4303665/?nrt=54|title= F1 extends Pirelli tyre supply deal to 2023|publisher=motorsport.com|accessdate= 25 November 2018}}</ref> and for the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Motocyclisme|FIM]] [[World Superbike Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/27072011/58/pirelli-supply-wsbk-tyres-2015.html|title=Pirelli supply wsbk tyres|publisher=Yahoo sport|accessdate= 21 February 2013}}</ref> Pirelli's headquarters are located in Milan's [[Bicocca (district of Milan)|Bicocca district]].\n\nPirelli is now solely a tire manufacturing company. In the past it has been involved in [[fashion]] and operated in [[renewable energy]] and [[sustainable mobility]].\n\nOn 4 October 2017, Pirelli returned to the Milan Stock Exchange<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pirelli-ipo/share-price-fall-deflates-pirellis-market-comeback-idUKKCN1C91AU|title=Share price fall deflates Pirelli's market comeback|last=Anzolin|first=Elisa|work=U.K.|access-date=2018-02-26|language=en-GB}}</ref> after focusing its business on pure consumer products (tires for car, motorcycles, bicycles) and related services, and separating the business of industrial tire.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.european-rubber-journal.com/2017/04/04/pirelli-separates-industrial-unit-become-pure-consumer-tire-company/|title=Pirelli separates from industrial tires unit to become \"pure consumer tire company\" \u2013 European Rubber Journal|date=2017-04-04|work=European Rubber Journal|access-date=2018-02-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nPirelli has published its [[Pirelli Calendar]] since 1964, which has featured the contributions of many famous photographers over the years such as [[Helmut Newton]], [[Steve McCurry]], [[Peter Lindbergh]], [[Richard Avedon]], [[Bruce Weber (photographer)|Bruce Weber]], [[Herb Ritts|Herb Rits]] and [[Annie Leibovitz]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Paolo Monti - Servizio fotografico (Milano, 1958) - BEIC 6338547.jpg|thumb|The [[Pirelli Tower]] in Milan in 1958, during construction, photographed by [[Paolo Monti]]]]\nFounded in [[Milan]] in 1872 by Giovanni Battista Pirelli, the company initially specialised in [[rubber]] and derivative processes and also made scuba diving [[rebreather]]s.<ref name=rebreather>{{Cite journal |author1=Coates, JK |author2=Kincaid, TC |author3=Lanphier, EH |title=Evaluation of the Pirelli Underwater Oxygen Breathing Equipment for Use in the Naval Service. |journal=[[United States Navy Experimental Diving Unit|Navy Experimental Diving Unit]] Technical Report |volume=NEDU-RR-2-52 |year=1952 |url=http://archive.rubicon-foundation.org/3393 |accessdate=16 March 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008071454/http://archive.rubicon-foundation.org/xmlui/handle/123456789/3393 |archive-date=8 October 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Thereafter, Pirelli's activities were primarily focused on the production of [[tire]] and [[Electrical cable|cable]]s (for [[energy]] and [[telecommunications]]). In 2005, Pirelli sold its cable division to [[Goldman Sachs]], which changed the new group's name to [[Prysmian]].\n\nIn the 1950s, Alberto Pirelli commissioned the building of a [[skyscraper]], [[Pirelli Tower]], in the same Milanese area that housed the very first Pirelli factory during the 19th century.<ref>Skyscrapers, Antonino Terranova, White Star Publishers, 2003 ({{ISBN|8880952307}})</ref>\n\nIn 1974, Pirelli invented the \"wide [[radial tire]]\", upon a request from the [[Lancia]] rally racing team for a tyre strong enough to withstand the power of the new [[Lancia Stratos]]. At that time, racing tires were either [[Slick tire|slick tires]] made with the [[cross ply]] technique (very wide tyres with a reduced sidewall height), or [[radial tire]], which were too narrow to withstand the Stratos' power and did not provide enough grip. Both were unusable for the Lancia Stratos, as the radials were destroyed within 10&nbsp;km, and the slicks too stiff. Lancia asked Pirelli for a solution, and in 1975 Pirelli created a wide tire with a reduced sidewall height like a slick, but with a radial structure.\n\nSubsequently, Porsche started using the same tires with the [[Porsche 911 Turbo]].\n\nIn 1988, Pirelli acquired the Armstrong Rubber Company, which was headquartered in [[New Haven, Connecticut]], for $190 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://connecticuthistory.org/armstrong-finds-a-niche-in-the-tire-market |title=Armstrong Finds a Niche in the Tire Market | publisher=Connecticut Humanities |accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Pirelli sold its terrestrial fibre optic cables business to [[Cisco Systems|Cisco]] and its optical components operations to [[Corning Inc.|Corning]], for 5 billion euro.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/cisco-taps-pirelli-for-optical-technology/|title=Cisco taps Pirelli for optical technology|work=CNET|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en}}</ref> It invested \u2013 through Olimpia -part of the resulting liquidity to become a majority shareholder in [[Telecom Italia]] in 2001,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2001/jul/30/citynews.media|title=Pirelli seizes Telecom Italia|last=Hepher|first=Tim|date=2001-07-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> maintaining this position until 2007.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/c44c1ef6-d1d0-11db-b921-000b5df10621.html?ft_site=falcon&desktop=true#axzz4igYZpn9S|title=Tronchetti/Telecom Italia|date=2007-03-14|work=Financial Times|access-date=2017-05-31|issn=0307-1766}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2002 the company started a range of Pirelli branded clothing, watches and eyewear.<ref>\n[http://www.pirelli.com/corporate/en/company/brand/ind-design/default.html official website]</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Pirelli sold its Cables, Energy Systems and Telecommunications assets to [[Goldman Sachs]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.penews.com/magazine/analysis/content/content/541211/restricted|title=Goldman Sachs buys Pirelli Cables for \u20ac1.3bn|website=www.penews.com|access-date=2017-05-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805124509/http://www.penews.com/magazine/analysis/content/content/541211/restricted|archive-date=5 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the newly formed company was named [[Prysmian Group|Prysmian]]. In the same year, 2005, Pirelli opened its first tire production plant in Shandong province, [[China]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tyrepress.com/2005/10/pirelli-opens-first-tyre-plant-in-china/|title=Pirelli Opens First Tyre Plant In China|date=2005-10-12|work=Tyrepress|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en-US}}</ref> This was the beginning of the group's production complex in the country.\n\nIn 2006, Pirelli chose [[Slatina, Romania|Slatina]] for its first tire production plant in [[Romania]], extending the facility in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.romania-insider.com/pirelli-to-turn-slatina-tyre-factory-in-romania-into-companys-biggest-plant-with-eur-160-mln|title=Pirelli to turn Slatina tyre factory in Romania into company's biggest plant with EUR 160 mln|work=Romania Insider|accessdate=18 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Pirelli completed its conversion to a pure [[List of tire companies|tire company]] by selling Pirelli Broadband Solutions<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/pirelli-broadband-idUKLDE69B11H20101012|title=Pirelli to sell broadband ops by end-Oct-source|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|work=Reuters UK|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en-GB}}</ref> and spinning off the real estate assets of Pirelli Re.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/pirelli-idUKLF59813520091026|title=DEALTALK-Pirelli seen reviving tyre, real estate split|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|work=Reuters UK|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en-GB}}</ref> Fondazione Pirelli was established in the same year to safeguard and celebrate the company's past and to promote business culture as an integral part of Italy's national cultural assets.\n\nIn March 2015, it was announced that Pirelli shareholders had accepted a \u20ac7.1 billion bid from ChemChina, together with Camfin and LTI, for the company.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news |title=ChemChina makes \u20ac7.1bn bid for Pirelli |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/mar/23/chemchina-makes-71bn-bid-for-italy-pirelli-tyre-maker |accessdate=23 March 2015 |work=The Guardian |agency=Reuters| date=23 March 2015}}</ref> The transaction was completed and the company was delisted in November 2015.<ref name=\"Delisting\">{{cite web| url=https://www.pirelli.com/corporate/en/investors/share_info/default.html| title=PIRELLI Shares \u2013 Information for Shareholders| date=November 2015| publisher=Pirelli| accessdate=6 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, it was announced that Pirelli returns to the world of cycling with a new road cycling tire range, Pzero Velo.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/2795/pirelli-returns-to-cycling-with-new-road-tyres|title=Pirelli returns to cycling with new road tyres|work=Cyclist|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, the company announced its intentions to sell up to 40 percent of its equity capital in an initial public offering as it plans to return to the Milan stock exchange in October.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pirelli-ipo/tiremaker-pirelli-to-offer-40-percent-of-share-capital-in-upcoming-ipo-idUSKCN1BF0JP|title=Tyremaker Pirelli to sell 40 percent stake in Milan market comeback|date=4 September 2017|work=Reuters|accessdate=2017-09-07}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019 Pirelli announced a new range of mountainbiking tires, called Scorpion.\n\n== Business areas ==\nPirelli is focused on the consumer business, producing tires for cars, motorcycles and bicycles.\n\n=== Car products range ===\nPZero: tires for ultra-high performance cars. including F1 vehicles\n\n[[Pirelli Cinturato|Cinturato]]: tires for high end cars.\n\nWinter: tires for low temperatures and snow.\n\nScorpion: tires for SUV and cross-over\n\n=== Moto products range ===\nDiablo: road and track tires.\n\nAngel: street and commuting tires.\n\nScorpion: road and off-road tires.\n\n=== Velo products range ===\nPZero Velo: road racing.\n\nCycl-e: urban and electric.\n\nScorpion: Mountainbike\n\n==Corporate affairs==\n\n===Major shareholders===\nPirelli shareholders<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://corporate.pirelli.com/corporate/en-ww/investors/shareholder-information/shareholder-structure|title=Shareholder Structure|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref> as of September 2019:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Shareholder\n! Stake %\n|-\n| Marco Polo International Italy (an intermediate holding company for [[ChemChina]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consob.it/web/consob-and-its-activities/listed-companies/documenti/assetti_proprietari/semestre1-2018/5109_Az.html?filedate=19/06/2018&sem=/documenti/assetti_proprietari/semestre1-2018/5109_Az.html&docid=0&link=Pie-chart+Capitale+ordinario%3D%2Fdocumenti%2Fassetti%2Fsemestre1-2018%2F5109_TOrdDich.html%3B+Pie-chart+Capitale+votante%3D%2Fdocumenti%2Fassetti%2Fsemestre1-2018%2F5109_TVotDich.html&nav=false&p_p_id=ConsobPubblicazioni_WAR_consobpubblicazioni_INSTANCE_zupz2C19u5Zz&p_p_state=maximized|title=Listed companies \u2013 Ownership|date=19 June 2018|accessdate=22 June 2018|publisher=CONSOB}}</ref>\n|45.52%\n|-\n|Camfin\n|10.10%\n|-\n|Long-Term Investments Luxembourg\n|6.24%\n|-\n|[[Institutional investor]]s\n|34.64%\n|-\n|[[Retail investor]]s\n|3.50%\n|}\n\n===Board of directors===\nThe list of Pirelli Board of Directors:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://corporate.pirelli.com/corporate/en-ww/governance/board-of-directors-and-corporate-bodies/board-of-directors|title=Pirelli Board of Directors|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Pirelli}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Position\n! Name\n|-\n| Chairman\n| Ning Gaoning\n|-\n| Executive Vice Chairman and CEO\n| [[Marco Tronchetti Provera]]\n|-\n| Director\n| Yang Xingqiang\n|-\n| Director\n| Bai XinPing\n|-\n|Director\n|Giorgio Luca Bruno\n|-\n|Director\n|Laura Cioli\n|-\n|Director\n|Domenico De Sole\n|-\n| Director\n| Ze'ev Goldberg\n|-\n| Director\n| Tao Haisu\n|-\n| Director\n| Marisa Pappalardo\n|-\n|Director\n|Cristina Scocchia\n|-\n| Director\n| Giovanni Tronchetti Provera\n|-\n|Director\n|Fan Xiaohua\n|-\n|Director\n|Wei Yintao\n|-\n|Director\n|Giovanni Lo Storto\n|}\n\n==Financial information==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Financial Data<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pirelli.com/mediaObject/corporate/documents/common/investors/agm/2014/Annual_Financial_Report_at_december_31_2013_Vol_01_ENG/original/Annual_Financial_Report_at_december_31_2013_Vol_01_ENG.pdf|title=Annual Report 2013|publisher=Pirelli & C. }}</ref>\n!2016\n(million \u20ac)\n!2015\n(million \u20ac)\n!2014\n(million \u20ac)\n! 2013\n(million \u20ac)\n! 2012\n(million \u20ac)\n! 2011\n(million \u20ac)\n! 2010\n(million \u20ac)\n! 2009\n(million \u20ac)\n|-\n| Net Sales\n|6,058\n|6,309\n|6,018\n| 6,146\n| 6,072\t\n| 5,655\t\n| 4,848\n| 4,067\n|-\n| Gross Operating Profit\n|1,183\n|1,242\n|1,168\n| 1,080\n| 1,064 (restated)\t\n| 807\n| 629\n| 453\n|-\n| EBIT\n|896.6 (Adjusted)\n|850.3\n|837.9\n| 791\n| 792 (restated)\t\n| 582\t\n| 408\n| 250\n|-\n| Net Income\n|147.6\n|(391)*\n|319\n| 306\n| 398\t\n| 441\n| 4\n| (23)\n|-\n| Net Invested Capital\n|10,224\n|4,089\n|4,273\n| 4,455\n| 4,427\n| 3,727\n| 3,281\n| 3,818\n|-\n| Equity\n|3,274\n|2,280\n|2,548\n| 2,437\n| 2,389\t\n| 2,192\t\n| 2,028\n| 2,495\n|-\n| Employees \n|37,050\n|36,753\n|37,561\n| 37,979\n| 37,338\n| 34,259\n| 29,573\n| 29,570\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki>The performance takes into account, as well as the deconsolidation of Venezuela, a non-recurring fiscal impact of 107.6 million euro linked to the devaluation of active deferred taxation by the Parent Group as a consequence of Pirelli\u2019s new financial status after its merger with Marco Polo Industrial Holding.\n\n==Marketing==\nThe [[Pirelli Calendar]] is published annually, featuring actresses and fashion models. The calendar also features the work of fashion photographers, including [[Richard Avedon]], [[Peter Lindbergh]], [[Annie Leibovitz]], and [[Patrick Demarchelier]].\n\nThe [[Pirelli Internetional Award|Pirelli ''Internet''ional Award]] is given annually for the best international multimedia involving the communication of science and technology conducted entirely on the Internet.\n\n\"Power is nothing without control\" was the well known slogan of Pirelli Tire Company, and was featured in numerous television and print advertisements.<ref>{{cite web |title=Power is nothing without control celebrates 25 years {{!}} Pirelli |url=https://www.pirelli.com/global/en-ww/life/power-is-nothing-without-control-celebrates-25-years |website=www.pirelli.com |accessdate=16 March 2020 |date=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nPirelli is the long-serving main sponsor of Italian football club [[Inter Milan]], having sponsored the Italian team since the [[1995\u201396 F.C. Internazionale Milano season|1995\u201396 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/51761|title=Inter and Pirelli extend historic partnership|publisher=inter.it|date=14 March 2016|accessdate=12 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Sponsorship==\n\n===Football===\nPirelli has a history of sponsoring football teams. Pirelli is well known for its long term primary sponsorship of the Italian football club [[Inter Milan]] since 1995. Pirelli previously appeared as a sponsor on the shirts of the Maltese football club [[Valletta F.C.|Valletta]] for a short time.\n\nIn reference to Brazil striker [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]]\u2019s usual [[goal celebration]] of both arms outstretched, Pirelli ran a 1998 commercial in which he replaced the figure of Christ from the [[Christ the Redeemer (statue)|''Christ the Redeemer'']] statue that towers over his home city of [[Rio de Janeiro]] while in an Inter Milan strip.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pirelli e le metamorfosi della pubblicit\u00e0 |url=https://www.corriere.it/cultura/17_giugno_21/pubblicita-con-la-maiuscola-fondazione-pirelli-corraini-5efebe1c-569c-11e7-a35b-7a875278503a.shtml |accessdate=19 September 2018 |work=Corriere Della Sera}}</ref> It was controversial with the Catholic Church.<ref name=\"Pirelli\">{{cite news |title=World Cup 2014: Brazil furious over Christ the Redeemer statue in Rio de Janeiro in Italian football colours |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/southamerica/brazil/10886269/World-Cup-2014-Brazil-furious-over-Christ-the-Redeemer-statue-in-Rio-de-Janeiro-in-Italian-football-colours.html |accessdate=19 September 2018 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nPirelli's sponsorship of football teams is not limited to Europe, South America is a key market and as a result successful clubs have also been sponsored by the tyre company. The [[Brazil]]ian team [[Palmeiras]], [[Uruguay]]an team [[Pe\u00f1arol]] and [[Argentina|Argentinian]] side [[Club Atl\u00e9tico V\u00e9lez S\u00e1rsfield|V\u00e9lez S\u00e1rsfield]] all had Pirelli as a shirt sponsor.\n\nWhen English football club [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion Football Club]] built their new stadium in 2005, Pirelli became the title sponsor of the new ground. This was because the new stadium, named [[Pirelli Stadium]] lies next to the Pirelli factory in [[Burton-upon-Trent]], [[Staffordshire]], England.\n\nIn 2009 Pirelli became the title sponsor of the [[Chinese Super League]] (CSL), China's top tier football league.\n\nIn 2012, the company become a major sponsor of the [[Russian Cup (football)|Russian Cup]].\n\n===Formula One===\nPirelli is currently the event title sponsor of the [[Spanish Grand Prix|Spanish]] and [[Hungarian Grand Prix|Hungarian]] Grands Prix and sponsored the [[2018 French Grand Prix]].\n\n===Rally===\nPirelli supported rally with their [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|FIA]] [[Pirelli Star Driver]] program as an initiative to support young rally drivers.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.autosport.com/wrc/news/130841/fia-planning-major-revamp-of-wrc-ladder|title=FIA plans major revamp of World Rally Championship ladder by 2019|magazine=Autosport|author=David Evans|accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== America's Cup ===\nPirelli is sponsor of [[Team New Zealand|Emirates Team New Zealand]] in the 35th [[America's Cup]] (2017).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/pirelli-boards-team-new-zealand|title=Pirelli boards Team New Zealand|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Winter Sports ===\nPirelli sponsors [[FIS Alpine World Ski Championships|Alpine World Ski Championship]] and [[Ice Hockey World Championships|Ice Hockey World Championship]] [[International Ice Hockey Federation|IIHF]] from 2017 to 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fis-ski.com/news-multimedia/news/article=pirelli-and-infront-seal-five-year-sponsorship-agreement-across-flagship-winter-sports-events.html|title=Pirelli and Infront seal five year sponsorship agreement across flagship winter sports events \u2013 FIS-SKI|website=FIS-SKI|language=en|access-date=2017-05-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171030215506/http://www.fis-ski.com/news-multimedia/news/article=pirelli-and-infront-seal-five-year-sponsorship-agreement-across-flagship-winter-sports-events.html|archive-date=30 October 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The company is also sponsor of the Italian Ski Team and of the Swiss Ski Team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://business.pirelli.com/global/en-ww/pirelli-sponsors-alpine-world-ski-championship-and-ice-hockey|title=Pirelli sponsors Alpine World Ski Championship and ice hockey from 2017 to 2021|website=business.pirelli.com|access-date=2017-05-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170614230543/http://business.pirelli.com/global/en-ww/pirelli-sponsors-alpine-world-ski-championship-and-ice-hockey|archive-date=14 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Motorsport==\nPirelli is the only allowed tyre brand in the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Motocyclisme|FIM]] [[World Superbike Championship]] since 2007 (along with its support classes, such as the [[Supersport World Championship]]).\nPirelli has also been awarded the contract for the control tyre supply in the [[British Superbike Championship]] from 2008 until at least 2010.<ref>[http://www.britishsuperbike.com/html/newsarticle.php?id=1203 British Superbikes 2007] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080320074840/http://www.britishsuperbike.com/html/newsarticle.php?id=1203 |date=20 March 2008 }}</ref>\nPirelli were also the official tyre supplier of the [[World Rally Championship]] from [[2008 World Rally Championship season|2008]] to [[2010 World Rally Championship season|2010]], until the company withdrew to focus on its Formula 1 commitments. Pirelli returned to the championship in [[2014 World Rally Championship season|2014]], however they only supply tyres for a few private teams as [[Michelin]] is the major tyre supplier. Pirelli was also supplied [[Grand-Am]] [[Rolex Sports Car Series]] from 2008 until at least 2010 before replaced by [[Continental AG]] in 2011. Pirelli is sponsor of rally and gymkhana driver [[Ken Block]]'s [[Hoonigan Racing Division]] since 2010.\n\nPirelli is the sole tyre supplier in [[Formula One]], following [[Bridgestone]]'s decision to withdraw from the role at the end of {{F1|2010}}.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Bridgestone to Cease Tire Supply to the FIA Formula One World Championship | url = http://bridgestone.com/corporate/news/2009110201.html | publisher = [[Bridgestone]] | date = 2 November 2009 | accessdate = 2 November 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20091104223536/http://bridgestone.com/corporate/news/2009110201.html | archivedate = 4 November 2009 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"WMSC230610\">{{cite web|title=World Motor Sport Council: 23 June 2010|url=http://www.fia.com/en-GB/mediacentre/pressreleases/wmsc/2010/Pages/wmsc_230610.aspx|work=fia.com|publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]|date=23 June 2010|accessdate=23 June 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626103652/http://www.fia.com/en-GB/mediacentre/pressreleases/wmsc/2010/Pages/wmsc_230610.aspx|archivedate=26 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Pirelli return to F1 after 20-year absence|url=http://www.f1fanatic.co.uk/2010/06/23/pirelli-return-to-f1-after-20-year-absence/|first=Keith|last=Collantine|work=F1 Fanatic|publisher=Keith Collantine|date=23 June 2010|accessdate=23 June 2010}}</ref> Pirelli previously competed in Formula One from {{F1|1950}}\u2013{{F1|1958}}, {{F1|1981}}\u2013{{F1|1986}} and {{F1|1989}}\u2013{{F1|1991}}. Pirelli has also supplied tyres for all [[FIA Formula 2 Championship]] and [[GP3 Series]] cars since 2011 and 2010 respectively.\n\nThe tyre manufacturer introduced a colour coding to recognize tyre compounds used by drivers during the racing weekend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.f1fanatic.co.uk/2011/03/18/pirelli-confirms-colours-tyres/|title=Pirelli confirms six different colours for tyres \u00b7 F1 Fanatic|date=2011-03-18|website=F1 Fanatic|access-date=2017-05-31}}</ref> For the benefit of the spectators at the track and the television audiences each compound has its own colour coding on the Pirelli and P Zero logos which appear on the sidewalls of the tyre. For the 2019 season, Pirelli reverted to using 3 colours to identify the dry weather tyres. However there still were 5 different compounds meaning that the same compound tyre can be represented by different colours throughout the season.\n\nPirelli were asked to design tyres that degraded rapidly in order to promote more pit stops and closer racing. At the end of the 2011 season, many F1 drivers praised Pirelli's comeback.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gpupdate.net/en/f1-news/271986/drivers-praise-pirelli-s-comeback-season/|title=Drivers praise Pirelli's comeback season|website=GPUpdate.net|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-06-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201131751/https://www.gpupdate.net/en/f1-news/271986/drivers-praise-pirelli-s-comeback-season/|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nControversy surrounded Pirelli's [[Formula 1 tyres]] as at the 2013 British Grand Prix seven Pirelli tyres failed: P\u00e9rez twice, Alonso, Hamilton, Gutierrez, Vergne, and Massa. Following a safety car period drivers were instructed to stay off the kerbs that were later found to be \"razor sharp\" and may have been the cause, but the president of the British Racing Drivers' Club rejected the idea that the kerbs could be at fault, saying that \"These kerbs have been in since 2009 and we have had thousands and thousands of cars go over these kerbs and they have been absolutely fine\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/23132957|title=BBC Sport \u2013 F1 boss Bernie Ecclestone dismisses talk of boycott|author=Andrew Benson|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> The incidents were described as \"unacceptable\" by F1 drivers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/23118249|title=BBC Sport \u2013 British GP: Lewis Hamilton says Pirelli tyre failures dangerous|author1=Lawrence Barretto  |author2=Andrew Benson |lastauthoramp=yes |work=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> It was later suggested that the cause of the tyre failures could be the teams putting them on the wrong side of the car. Pirelli stressed that the tyres are of an asymmetrical construction and are not interchangeable, and that if they are used correctly, they do not pose a threat to safety.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pirelli.com/tyre/ww/en/news/2013/07/02/pirelli-explanation-on-silverstone-facts-and-next-races/|title=Pirelli, explanation on Silverstone' facts and next races|work=pirelli.com|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> Pirelli changed the construction of the tyres to prevent further incidents, switching to kevlar belts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.f1fanatic.co.uk/2013/07/02/pirelli-to-use-prototype-tyres-for-german-grand-prix/|title=Kevlar belt tyres for Germany, new tyres for Hungary \u00b7 F1 Fanatic|date=2013-07-02|website=F1 Fanatic|access-date=2017-05-31}}</ref>\n\nDuring the second practice of the 2013 Belgian Grand Prix, two tyres failed: Vettel and Alonso. One senior figure at Pirelli described the failures as a \"big concern\", whilst Pirelli's motorsport director Paul Hembery admitted the tyre failures were \"a worry for the sport\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/23816972|title=BBC Sport \u2013 Belgian GP: Drivers demand reassurance Pirelli tyres are safe|author=Andrew Benson|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> Following these issues, just one day later [[Michelin]] announced that they could replace Pirelli as the tyre supplier for 2014. In October 2013 [[Fernando Alonso]] complained that \"the quality of the tyres is very on the limit\", and that they \"will not do 5km\". Pirelli motorsport director Paul Hembery said: \"Of course Alonso is one of the great F1 drivers, so to hear such comments is disappointing and below the standards you would expect from such a champion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/24409735|title=BBC Sport \u2013 Fernando Alonso criticises Pirelli tyres after Korean GP qualifying|author=Andrew Benson|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> In the Korean Grand Prix P\u00e9rez locked a front tyre heavily and then suffered a dramatic failure on the subsequent long straight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/24420547|title=BBC Sport \u2013 Korean GP: perfection from Vettel, less so from the tyres|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> Pirelli hit controversy at the Indian Grand Prix where they requested the teams run the tyres a limited number of laps due to their fragility. One senior engineer at a top team said this was the worst blistering ever experienced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/24690717|title=BBC Sport \u2013 Indian GP: Pirelli wants limited tyre running on safety grounds|author=Andrew Benson|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn pre-season testing for the 2014 season the tyre on Rosberg's car failed, sending Rosberg into a {{convert|200|mph|0|abbr=on}} spin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/25449812|title=BBC Sport \u2013 Nico Rosberg suffers tyre failure in Bahrain Pirelli test|author=Andrew Benson|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> The incident prompted considerable alarm, and Pirelli stated that the tyre \"will not be proposed again\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www1.skysports.com/f1/news/12472/9080138/pirelli-tyre-which-failed-on-rosbergs-car-was-prototype-that-wont-be-used-again |title=Pirelli: 'Prototype tyre which failed on Nico Rosberg's car won't be used again' | work=Sky Sports}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2014 Pirelli signed a contract with the FIA to supply tyres to Formula One for the 2014, 2015 and 2016 seasons.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/112150 |title=Pirelli concludes new Formula 1 tyre supply deal| work=Autosport | date=16 January 2014}}</ref> Later in 2014 [[Lewis Hamilton]] described the Pirelli wet weather tyres as \"They're not great tyres. That's no secret\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/29634110|title=BBC Sport \u2013 Lewis Hamilton & Sebastian Vettel call for better wet-weather tyres|author=Andrew Benson|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> \"These are comments by drivers that have not been made in an official way to us. Of course, if Pirelli was requested by the teams and the FIA to reconsider the technical capability of the wet tyre, Pirelli would do it immediately\" was the comment of Pirelli's motorsport director Paul Hembery.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAt the 2015 Belgian Grand Prix, during practice, Rosberg suffered a dangerous tyre delamination at {{convert|200|mph|0|abbr=on}}. Rosberg said the incident was \"quite a shock\".  During the subsequent drivers' briefing, double world champion Lewis Hamilton raised concerns about tyre safety following the high-speed blow-out suffered by teammate Nico Rosberg. Concerns were also brought up by four-time world champion Vettel, and double world champion Alonso. Pirelli relied on race director, Charlie Whiting, to defend Pirelli's record in the meeting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/34021994|title=Nico Rosberg tyre failure: Hamilton and Alonso raise concerns|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> During the race a tyre on Vettel's car suffered from a blowout at {{convert|200|mph|0|abbr=on}}. The four time world champion described the failure an \"unacceptable\", and added that Pirelli's tendency to blame failures either on debris on track or a driver going over a kerb for tyre failures was incorrect, confirming that \"I didn't go off the track and out of the blue the tyre explodes\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/34035036|title=Sebastian Vettel says Pirelli tyre failure unacceptable|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> Following the race Rosberg was critical of the poor quality of Pirelli tyres, saying \"Vettel exploding his tyre is really poor. It shouldn't happen and that it keeps on happening, in other categories as well and today with us, and with me on Friday both of us were just so lucky\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/f1/news/24182/9962863/vettel-launches-pirelli-attack|title=Sebastian Vettel & Nico Rosberg round on Pirelli after tyre blowouts|author=James Galloway|work=Sky Sports}}</ref> The [[Grand Prix Drivers' Association]] chairman said: \"We need to stop the sudden explosions.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/34063824|title=Belgian Grand Prix: Drivers demand end of blowouts|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> Immediately after the race Pirelli claimed that excessive wear caused the blowout, blaming Ferrari for running the tyre too long. However, following a more detailed analysis Pirelli said that in fact wear was not to blame, but instead a cut had caused the tyre failure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/120596|title=Pirelli reveals F1 tyre investigation findings from Belgian GP|author=Ian Parkes|date=3 September 2015|work=AUTOSPORT.com}}</ref> To counteract further problems at the next Grand Prix, Monza, Pirelli wanted to insist that teams run the tyres at high pressure, beyond their design parameters. However, double world champion Lewis Hamilton described these rules as a \"disaster\" and double world champion Fernando Alonso described them as \"strange\" so Pirelli was forced to backtrack on their proposal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/34141910|title=Pirelli relaxes tyre limits after Lewis Hamilton & Alonso complaints|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> After these comments, Pirelli attempted to censor the drivers by asking them to not criticise the tyres in public in the future.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/34155703|title=Italian GP: Drivers told to keep worries over Pirelli tyres private|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe situation did not improve at the next Grand Prix at Monza. Here, Pirelli reported a higher than expected number of cuts forming in the tyres.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/120670|title=Italian GP: Pirelli reports high number of F1 tyre cuts at Monza|author1=Dieter Rencken  |author2=Lawrence Barretto |lastauthoramp=yes |date=6 September 2015|work=AUTOSPORT.com}}</ref> During the race, one of Hamilton's tyres dropped below the regulation pressure dictated by Pirelli, despite the tyre having been prepared by a Pirelli technician.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/formula1/32543096|title=Lewis Hamilton wins in Italy \u2013 reaction \u2013 BBC Sport|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> Neither Mercedes nor Hamilton were punished for the infringement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/34168014|title=Lewis Hamilton keeps Italian GP win after stewards' investigation|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> Later in 2016, the necessity to run Pirelli tyres at high pressure was described as a \"joke\" by triple world champion Lewis Hamilton, world champion Jenson Button, and world championship runner-up Felipe Massa.<ref>https://www.jamesallenonf1.com/2016/09/pirelli-starting-to-lower-minimum-f1-tyre-pressures-airs-concerns-over-2017-testing/</ref>\n\nAbove any criticisms, in 2016 the renewal of the contract as sole supplier was strongly supported by the protagonists of the Formula 1 circus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/formulaone/article-3173665/Christian-Horner-hopes-Pirelli-s-sole-tyre-F1-supplier-deal-extended-2016-despite-Michelin-interest.html|title=Horner hopes Pirelli's sole tyre F1 deal is extended beyond 2016|work=Mail Online|access-date=2017-05-31}}</ref>\n\nA number of changes to the [[Formula One|Formula 1]] tyres were introduced for the 2017 season. The most obvious visual difference was an increase of width by 25%, both front and rear, increasing from 245 to 305mm at the front and 325 to 405mm at the rear. The actual rim size remained unchanged from the traditional 13 inches.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/125375|title=Formula 1 2017 tyre rules: The key questions and Pirelli's plans|last=Parkes|first=Ian|work=Autosport.com|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThis is part of a package of measures expected to cut lap times by around five seconds relative to 2015: although the improvement might be even bigger.\n\nMost of that extra speed has been found through corners, as the cars have got wider and will generate at least 20% more downforce compared to last year thanks to bigger wings and increased aerodynamics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/38530543|title=2017 season: F1 looks back for its future with faster, wider cars|date=2017-01-09|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThese faster cornering speeds\u2014to the extent that some corners have now effectively become straights, already leading to circuit modifications\u2014have imposed significantly increased loads on the tyres, meaning that there is a completely new philosophy behind Pirelli\u2019s 2017 range. Having followed the brief to provide deliberate degradation for the past six seasons, there is now a new directive to make tyres with less degradation that are more resistant to overheating for the latest generation of much faster cars.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/127693|title=New Formula 1 tyres for 2017 have 'very low degradation'|last=Noble|first=Roberto Chinchero and Jonathan|work=Autosport.com|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en}}</ref> As a result, the tyre structure and compounds are brand new.\n\n==Overseas investment==\nIn April 2012, Pirelli & C. SpA signed joint venture agreement with [[Indonesia]]n counterpart PT Astra Autoparts a subsidiary of PT [[Astra International]] for the construction of a motorcycle tyre plant with a total investment of $120 million. 60 percent shares will be held by Pirelli. Pirelli hoped to strengthen its presence in the largest motorcycle market in the world, the [[Southeast Asia]] region which has 250 million motorcycles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/04/25/indonesia-welcomes-pirelli-italian-touch-local-shoes.html |title=Indonesia welcomes Pirelli, Italian touch for local shoes |date=25 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Audio system==\nIn July 2018, Pirelli launched a F1 wheel shaped Bluetooth speaker, P Zero Sound.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bruce |first1=Chris |title=Pirelli Design Launches Bluetooth Speaker That Looks Like F1 Wheel |url=https://www.motor1.com/news/258609/pirelli-design-tire-bluetooth-speaker/ |website=Motor1.com |accessdate=16 March 2020 |language=en |date=25 July 2018}}</ref> The Bluetooth speaker measures 12.9-inches in diameter, weighs 21 pounds and has a 100-watt amplifier, a 100mm midwoofer, a 25mm tweeter and also offers Bluetooth 4.0 with AptX for wireless connectivity. IXOOST<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ixoost.it/|title=IXOOST official site|access-date=2018-07-31}}</ref> is the manufacturer of P Zero Sound speaker, which majorly manufactures Motorsports-themed audio systems. The wheel shaped speaker costs \u20ac2400, which is equivalent to about $2,800.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Italy|Companies}}\n* [[List of Italian companies]]\n* [[Formula One tyres]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://www.pirellityre.com PirelliTyre.com] Pirelli Tyres Worldwide\n*[http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/41/41369.html Yahoo!] Pirelli & C. S.p.A. Company Profile\n{{Automotive industry in Italy}}\n{{Pirelli & C. SpA}}\n{{Rubber}}\n{{FTSE MIB companies}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Pirelli| ]]\n[[Category:Automotive companies of Italy]]\n[[Category:Tire manufacturers of Italy]]\n[[Category:Cycle parts manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1872]]\n[[Category:Rebreather makers]]\n[[Category:Italian brands]]\n[[Category:Watch manufacturing companies of Italy]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in Italy]]\n[[Category:1872 establishments in Italy]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Borsa Italiana]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|45.5195317|9.2111299|display=title}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Pirelli & C. [[Societ\u00e0 per azioni|S.p.A.]]\n| logo = Logo Pirelli.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n| image = Pirelli headquarters.jpg \n| image_size = 250px\n| image_caption = Pirelli headquarters as seen in 2004\n| type = [[Societ\u00e0 per azioni]]\n| traded_as = {{BIT|IT0005278236|PIRC}}\n| ISIN = IT0005278236\n| founder = Giovanni Battista Pirelli\n| hq_location_city = Milan\n| hq_location_country =  Italy\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = [[Ning Gaoning]] ([[Chairman]])<br />[[Marco Tronchetti Provera]] ([[Chairman|Executive Vice Chairman]] and [[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]])\n| industry = [[Automotive]]\n| products = [[Tyres]] for [[car]], [[motorcycle]]s and [[cycling]]\n| revenue = \u20ac5.195 billion <small>(2018)</small><ref name=\"Highlights\">{{Cite web|url=https://corporate.pirelli.com/corporate/en-ww/investors/annual-report-2018|work=Pirelli|title=Highlights|language=en}}</ref>\n| operating_income = \u20ac703 million <small>(2018)</small><ref name=\"Highlights\" />\n| net_income = \u20ac442 million <small>(2018)</small><ref name=\"Highlights\" />\n| assets = \n| equity = \n| num_employees = 31,489 <small>(2018)</small>\n| subsid = Pirelli Tyre S.p.A.\n| foundation = {{start date and age|1872|df=yes}}<br>[[Milan]], [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]]\n| homepage = [http://www.pirelli.com pirelli.com]\n| parent = \n| owner = [[ChemChina]] (45.5%)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pirelli-ipo/chemchina-gave-up-pirelli-control-to-show-its-market-friendly-face-pirelli-ceo-idUSKCN1BT0YB|title=ChemChina gave up Pirelli control to show its market friendly face: Pirelli CEO|work=Reuters|author=Agnieszka Flak|author2=Elisa Anzolin|accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref><br>[[Marco Tronchetti Provera]] (10.05%)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/pirelli-ipo/pirelli-ceo-says-core-shareholders-have-no-plans-to-sell-stakes-idUSI6N1D100W|title=Pirelli CEO says core shareholders have no plans to sell stakes|work=Reuters|accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Pirelli & C. S.p.A.''' is an Italian [[multinational company]] based in [[Milan]], [[Italy]], listed on the [[Milan Stock Exchange]] since 1922,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.borsaitaliana.it/companyprofile/en/214.pdf|title=Pirelli Company Profile|publisher=Borsa Italiana|accessdate=21 February 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301192412/http://www.borsaitaliana.it/companyprofile/en/214.pdf|archivedate=1 March 2014}}</ref> with a temporary privatization period by the consortium led by the Chinese state-owned enterprise [[ChemChina]]. The company is the 5th<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tyrepress.com/leading-tyre-manufacturers/|title=Leading tyre manufacturers|date=2013-09-26|work=Tyrepress|access-date=2018-07-17|language=en-GB}}</ref> largest [[tire]] manufacturer behind [[Bridgestone]], [[Michelin]],  [[Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company|Goodyear]] and [[Continental AG|Continental]], and is focused on the consumer business (tires for cars, motorcycles and bicycles). It is present in [[Europe]], [[Asia-Pacific|the Asia-Pacific]], [[Latin America]], [[North American Free Trade Agreement|North America]] and ex-USSR, operating commercially in over 160 countries. It has 19 manufacturing sites<ref>{{cite web|url=http://corporate.pirelli.com/corporate/en-ww/aboutus/about-us|title=Pirelli \u2013 About us|last=|first=|date=|website=}}</ref> in 13 countries and a network of around 14,600 distributors and retailers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/psi-dotcom-prd/corporate/3149_2018.05.14_Company_Presentation+v15_LINKS.pdf|title=Pirelli Company Presentation|publisher=Pirelli|accessdate=18 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nPirelli has been sponsoring sport competitions since 1907 and is the exclusive tire supplier for the [[Grand-Am]] [[Rolex Sports Car Series]] for 2008\u20132010, [[FIA Formula One World Championship]] for 2011\u20132023<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/pirelli-tyre-supply-deal-2023/4303665/?nrt=54|title= F1 extends Pirelli tyre supply deal to 2023|publisher=motorsport.com|accessdate= 25 November 2018}}</ref> and for the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Motocyclisme|FIM]] [[World Superbike Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/27072011/58/pirelli-supply-wsbk-tyres-2015.html|title=Pirelli supply wsbk tyres|publisher=Yahoo sport|accessdate= 21 February 2013}}</ref> Pirelli's headquarters are located in Milan's [[Bicocca (district of Milan)|Bicocca district]].\n\nPirelli is now solely a tire manufacturing company. In the past it has been involved in [[fashion]] and operated in [[renewable energy]] and [[sustainable mobility]].\n\nOn 4 October 2017, Pirelli returned to the Milan Stock Exchange<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-pirelli-ipo/share-price-fall-deflates-pirellis-market-comeback-idUKKCN1C91AU|title=Share price fall deflates Pirelli's market comeback|last=Anzolin|first=Elisa|work=U.K.|access-date=2018-02-26|language=en-GB}}</ref> after focusing its business on pure consumer products (tires for car, motorcycles, bicycles) and related services, and separating the business of industrial tire.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.european-rubber-journal.com/2017/04/04/pirelli-separates-industrial-unit-become-pure-consumer-tire-company/|title=Pirelli separates from industrial tires unit to become \"pure consumer tire company\" \u2013 European Rubber Journal|date=2017-04-04|work=European Rubber Journal|access-date=2018-02-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nPirelli has published its [[Pirelli Calendar]] since 1964, which has featured the contributions of many famous photographers over the years such as [[Helmut Newton]], [[Steve McCurry]], [[Peter Lindbergh]], [[Richard Avedon]], [[Bruce Weber (photographer)|Bruce Weber]], [[Herb Ritts|Herb Rits]] and [[Annie Leibovitz]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Paolo Monti - Servizio fotografico (Milano, 1958) - BEIC 6338547.jpg|thumb|The [[Pirelli Tower]] in Milan in 1958, during construction, photographed by [[Paolo Monti]]]]\nFounded in [[Milan]] in 1872 by Giovanni Battista Pirelli, the company initially specialised in [[rubber]] and derivative processes and also made scuba diving [[rebreather]]s.<ref name=rebreather>{{Cite journal |author1=Coates, JK |author2=Kincaid, TC |author3=Lanphier, EH |title=Evaluation of the Pirelli Underwater Oxygen Breathing Equipment for Use in the Naval Service. |journal=[[United States Navy Experimental Diving Unit|Navy Experimental Diving Unit]] Technical Report |volume=NEDU-RR-2-52 |year=1952 |url=http://archive.rubicon-foundation.org/3393 |accessdate=16 March 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141008071454/http://archive.rubicon-foundation.org/xmlui/handle/123456789/3393 |archive-date=8 October 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Thereafter, Pirelli's activities were primarily focused on the production of [[tire]] and [[Electrical cable|cable]]s (for [[energy]] and [[telecommunications]]). In 2005, Pirelli sold its cable division to [[Goldman Sachs]], which changed the new group's name to [[Prysmian]].\n\nIn the 1950s, Alberto Pirelli commissioned the building of a [[skyscraper]], [[Pirelli Tower]], in the same Milanese area that housed the very first Pirelli factory during the 19th century.<ref>Skyscrapers, Antonino Terranova, White Star Publishers, 2003 ({{ISBN|8880952307}})</ref>\n\nIn 1974, Pirelli invented the \"wide [[radial tire]]\", upon a request from the [[Lancia]] rally racing team for a tyre strong enough to withstand the power of the new [[Lancia Stratos]]. At that time, racing tires were either [[Slick tire|slick tires]] made with the [[cross ply]] technique (very wide tyres with a reduced sidewall height), or [[radial tire]], which were too narrow to withstand the Stratos' power and did not provide enough grip. Both were unusable for the Lancia Stratos, as the radials were destroyed within 10&nbsp;km, and the slicks too stiff. Lancia asked Pirelli for a solution, and in 1975 Pirelli created a wide tire with a reduced sidewall height like a slick, but with a radial structure.\n\nSubsequently, Porsche started using the same tires with the [[Porsche 911 Turbo]].\n\nIn 1988, Pirelli acquired the Armstrong Rubber Company, which was headquartered in [[New Haven, Connecticut]], for $190 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://connecticuthistory.org/armstrong-finds-a-niche-in-the-tire-market |title=Armstrong Finds a Niche in the Tire Market | publisher=Connecticut Humanities |accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Pirelli sold its terrestrial fibre optic cables business to [[Cisco Systems|Cisco]] and its optical components operations to [[Corning Inc.|Corning]], for 5 billion euro.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/cisco-taps-pirelli-for-optical-technology/|title=Cisco taps Pirelli for optical technology|work=CNET|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en}}</ref> It invested \u2013 through Olimpia -part of the resulting liquidity to become a majority shareholder in [[Telecom Italia]] in 2001,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2001/jul/30/citynews.media|title=Pirelli seizes Telecom Italia|last=Hepher|first=Tim|date=2001-07-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> maintaining this position until 2007.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/c44c1ef6-d1d0-11db-b921-000b5df10621.html?ft_site=falcon&desktop=true#axzz4igYZpn9S|title=Tronchetti/Telecom Italia|date=2007-03-14|work=Financial Times|access-date=2017-05-31|issn=0307-1766}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2002 the company started a range of Pirelli branded clothing, watches and eyewear.<ref>\n[http://www.pirelli.com/corporate/en/company/brand/ind-design/default.html official website]</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Pirelli sold its Cables, Energy Systems and Telecommunications assets to [[Goldman Sachs]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.penews.com/magazine/analysis/content/content/541211/restricted|title=Goldman Sachs buys Pirelli Cables for \u20ac1.3bn|website=www.penews.com|access-date=2017-05-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805124509/http://www.penews.com/magazine/analysis/content/content/541211/restricted|archive-date=5 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the newly formed company was named [[Prysmian Group|Prysmian]]. In the same year, 2005, Pirelli opened its first tire production plant in Shandong province, [[China]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tyrepress.com/2005/10/pirelli-opens-first-tyre-plant-in-china/|title=Pirelli Opens First Tyre Plant In China|date=2005-10-12|work=Tyrepress|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en-US}}</ref> This was the beginning of the group's production complex in the country.\n\nIn 2006, Pirelli chose [[Slatina, Romania|Slatina]] for its first tire production plant in [[Romania]], extending the facility in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.romania-insider.com/pirelli-to-turn-slatina-tyre-factory-in-romania-into-companys-biggest-plant-with-eur-160-mln|title=Pirelli to turn Slatina tyre factory in Romania into company's biggest plant with EUR 160 mln|work=Romania Insider|accessdate=18 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Pirelli completed its conversion to a pure [[List of tire companies|tire company]] by selling Pirelli Broadband Solutions<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/pirelli-broadband-idUKLDE69B11H20101012|title=Pirelli to sell broadband ops by end-Oct-source|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|work=Reuters UK|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en-GB}}</ref> and spinning off the real estate assets of Pirelli Re.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/pirelli-idUKLF59813520091026|title=DEALTALK-Pirelli seen reviving tyre, real estate split|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|work=Reuters UK|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en-GB}}</ref> Fondazione Pirelli was established in the same year to safeguard and celebrate the company's past and to promote business culture as an integral part of Italy's national cultural assets.\n\nIn March 2015, it was announced that Pirelli shareholders had accepted a \u20ac7.1 billion bid from ChemChina, together with Camfin and LTI, for the company.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news |title=ChemChina makes \u20ac7.1bn bid for Pirelli |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/mar/23/chemchina-makes-71bn-bid-for-italy-pirelli-tyre-maker |accessdate=23 March 2015 |work=The Guardian |agency=Reuters| date=23 March 2015}}</ref> The transaction was completed and the company was delisted in November 2015.<ref name=\"Delisting\">{{cite web| url=https://www.pirelli.com/corporate/en/investors/share_info/default.html| title=PIRELLI Shares \u2013 Information for Shareholders| date=November 2015| publisher=Pirelli| accessdate=6 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, it was announced that Pirelli returns to the world of cycling with a new road cycling tire range, Pzero Velo.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cyclist.co.uk/news/2795/pirelli-returns-to-cycling-with-new-road-tyres|title=Pirelli returns to cycling with new road tyres|work=Cyclist|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, the company announced its intentions to sell up to 40 percent of its equity capital in an initial public offering as it plans to return to the Milan stock exchange in October.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pirelli-ipo/tiremaker-pirelli-to-offer-40-percent-of-share-capital-in-upcoming-ipo-idUSKCN1BF0JP|title=Tyremaker Pirelli to sell 40 percent stake in Milan market comeback|date=4 September 2017|work=Reuters|accessdate=2017-09-07}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019 Pirelli announced a new range of mountainbiking tires, called Scorpion.\n\n== Business areas ==\nPirelli is focused on the consumer business, producing tires for cars, motorcycles and bicycles.\n\n=== Car products range ===\nPZero: tires for ultra-high performance cars. including F1 vehicles\n\n[[Pirelli Cinturato|Cinturato]]: tires for high end cars.\n\nWinter: tires for low temperatures and snow.\n\nScorpion: tires for SUV and cross-over\n\n=== Moto products range ===\nDiablo: road and track tires.\n\nAngel: street and commuting tires.\n\nScorpion: road and off-road tires.\n\n=== Velo products range ===\nPZero Velo: road racing.\n\nCycl-e: urban and electric.\n\nScorpion: Mountainbike\n\n==Corporate affairs==\n\n===Major shareholders===\nPirelli shareholders<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://corporate.pirelli.com/corporate/en-ww/investors/shareholder-information/shareholder-structure|title=Shareholder Structure|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref> as of September 2019:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Shareholder\n! Stake %\n|-\n| Marco Polo International Italy (an intermediate holding company for [[ChemChina]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consob.it/web/consob-and-its-activities/listed-companies/documenti/assetti_proprietari/semestre1-2018/5109_Az.html?filedate=19/06/2018&sem=/documenti/assetti_proprietari/semestre1-2018/5109_Az.html&docid=0&link=Pie-chart+Capitale+ordinario%3D%2Fdocumenti%2Fassetti%2Fsemestre1-2018%2F5109_TOrdDich.html%3B+Pie-chart+Capitale+votante%3D%2Fdocumenti%2Fassetti%2Fsemestre1-2018%2F5109_TVotDich.html&nav=false&p_p_id=ConsobPubblicazioni_WAR_consobpubblicazioni_INSTANCE_zupz2C19u5Zz&p_p_state=maximized|title=Listed companies \u2013 Ownership|date=19 June 2018|accessdate=22 June 2018|publisher=CONSOB}}</ref>\n|45.52%\n|-\n|Camfin\n|10.10%\n|-\n|Long-Term Investments Luxembourg\n|6.24%\n|-\n|[[Institutional investor]]s\n|34.64%\n|-\n|[[Retail investor]]s\n|3.50%\n|}\n\n===Board of directors===\nThe list of Pirelli Board of Directors:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://corporate.pirelli.com/corporate/en-ww/governance/board-of-directors-and-corporate-bodies/board-of-directors|title=Pirelli Board of Directors|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Pirelli}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Position\n! Name\n|-\n| Chairman\n| Ning Gaoning\n|-\n| Executive Vice Chairman and CEO\n| [[Marco Tronchetti Provera]]\n|-\n| Director\n| Yang Xingqiang\n|-\n| Director\n| Bai XinPing\n|-\n|Director\n|Giorgio Luca Bruno\n|-\n|Director\n|Laura Cioli\n|-\n|Director\n|Domenico De Sole\n|-\n| Director\n| Ze'ev Goldberg\n|-\n| Director\n| Tao Haisu\n|-\n| Director\n| Marisa Pappalardo\n|-\n|Director\n|Cristina Scocchia\n|-\n| Director\n| Giovanni Tronchetti Provera\n|-\n|Director\n|Fan Xiaohua\n|-\n|Director\n|Wei Yintao\n|-\n|Director\n|Giovanni Lo Storto\n|}\n\n==Financial information==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Financial Data<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pirelli.com/mediaObject/corporate/documents/common/investors/agm/2014/Annual_Financial_Report_at_december_31_2013_Vol_01_ENG/original/Annual_Financial_Report_at_december_31_2013_Vol_01_ENG.pdf|title=Annual Report 2013|publisher=Pirelli & C. }}</ref>\n!2016\n(million \u20ac)\n!2015\n(million \u20ac)\n!2014\n(million \u20ac)\n! 2013\n(million \u20ac)\n! 2012\n(million \u20ac)\n! 2011\n(million \u20ac)\n! 2010\n(million \u20ac)\n! 2009\n(million \u20ac)\n|-\n| Net Sales\n|6,058\n|6,309\n|6,018\n| 6,146\n| 6,072\t\n| 5,655\t\n| 4,848\n| 4,067\n|-\n| Gross Operating Profit\n|1,183\n|1,242\n|1,168\n| 1,080\n| 1,064 (restated)\t\n| 807\n| 629\n| 453\n|-\n| EBIT\n|896.6 (Adjusted)\n|850.3\n|837.9\n| 791\n| 792 (restated)\t\n| 582\t\n| 408\n| 250\n|-\n| Net Income\n|147.6\n|(391)*\n|319\n| 306\n| 398\t\n| 441\n| 4\n| (23)\n|-\n| Net Invested Capital\n|10,224\n|4,089\n|4,273\n| 4,455\n| 4,427\n| 3,727\n| 3,281\n| 3,818\n|-\n| Equity\n|3,274\n|2,280\n|2,548\n| 2,437\n| 2,389\t\n| 2,192\t\n| 2,028\n| 2,495\n|-\n| Employees \n|37,050\n|36,753\n|37,561\n| 37,979\n| 37,338\n| 34,259\n| 29,573\n| 29,570\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki>The performance takes into account, as well as the deconsolidation of Venezuela, a non-recurring fiscal impact of 107.6 million euro linked to the devaluation of active deferred taxation by the Parent Group as a consequence of Pirelli\u2019s new financial status after its merger with Marco Polo Industrial Holding.\n\n==Marketing==\nThe [[Pirelli Calendar]] is published annually, featuring actresses and fashion models. The calendar also features the work of fashion photographers, including [[Richard Avedon]], [[Peter Lindbergh]], [[Annie Leibovitz]], and [[Patrick Demarchelier]].\n\nThe [[Pirelli Internetional Award|Pirelli ''Internet''ional Award]] is given annually for the best international multimedia involving the communication of science and technology conducted entirely on the Internet.\n\n\"Power is nothing without control\" was the well known slogan of Pirelli Tyre Company, and was featured in numerous television and print advertisements.<ref>{{cite web |title=Power is nothing without control celebrates 25 years {{!}} Pirelli |url=https://www.pirelli.com/global/en-ww/life/power-is-nothing-without-control-celebrates-25-years |website=www.pirelli.com |accessdate=16 March 2020 |date=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nPirelli is the long-serving main sponsor of Italian football club [[Inter Milan]], having sponsored the Italian team since the [[1995\u201396 F.C. Internazionale Milano season|1995\u201396 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/51761|title=Inter and Pirelli extend historic partnership|publisher=inter.it|date=14 March 2016|accessdate=12 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Sponsorship==\n\n===Football===\nPirelli has a history of sponsoring football teams. Pirelli is well known for its long term primary sponsorship of the Italian football club [[Inter Milan]] since 1995. Pirelli previously appeared as a sponsor on the shirts of the Maltese football club [[Valletta F.C.|Valletta]] for a short time.\n\nIn reference to Brazil striker [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]]\u2019s usual [[goal celebration]] of both arms outstretched, Pirelli ran a 1998 commercial in which he replaced the figure of Christ from the [[Christ the Redeemer (statue)|''Christ the Redeemer'']] statue that towers over his home city of [[Rio de Janeiro]] while in an Inter Milan strip.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pirelli e le metamorfosi della pubblicit\u00e0 |url=https://www.corriere.it/cultura/17_giugno_21/pubblicita-con-la-maiuscola-fondazione-pirelli-corraini-5efebe1c-569c-11e7-a35b-7a875278503a.shtml |accessdate=19 September 2018 |work=Corriere Della Sera}}</ref> It was controversial with the Catholic Church.<ref name=\"Pirelli\">{{cite news |title=World Cup 2014: Brazil furious over Christ the Redeemer statue in Rio de Janeiro in Italian football colours |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/southamerica/brazil/10886269/World-Cup-2014-Brazil-furious-over-Christ-the-Redeemer-statue-in-Rio-de-Janeiro-in-Italian-football-colours.html |accessdate=19 September 2018 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\nPirelli's sponsorship of football teams is not limited to Europe, South America is a key market and as a result successful clubs have also been sponsored by the tyre company. The [[Brazil]]ian team [[Palmeiras]], [[Uruguay]]an team [[Pe\u00f1arol]] and [[Argentina|Argentinian]] side [[Club Atl\u00e9tico V\u00e9lez S\u00e1rsfield|V\u00e9lez S\u00e1rsfield]] all had Pirelli as a shirt sponsor.\n\nWhen English football club [[Burton Albion F.C.|Burton Albion Football Club]] built their new stadium in 2005, Pirelli became the title sponsor of the new ground. This was because the new stadium, named [[Pirelli Stadium]] lies next to the Pirelli factory in [[Burton-upon-Trent]], [[Staffordshire]], England.\n\nIn 2009 Pirelli became the title sponsor of the [[Chinese Super League]] (CSL), China's top tier football league.\n\nIn 2012, the company become a major sponsor of the [[Russian Cup (football)|Russian Cup]].\n\n===Formula One===\nPirelli is currently the event title sponsor of the [[Spanish Grand Prix|Spanish]] and [[Hungarian Grand Prix|Hungarian]] Grands Prix and sponsored the [[2018 French Grand Prix]].\n\n===Rally===\nPirelli supported rally with their [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|FIA]] [[Pirelli Star Driver]] program as an initiative to support young rally drivers.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.autosport.com/wrc/news/130841/fia-planning-major-revamp-of-wrc-ladder|title=FIA plans major revamp of World Rally Championship ladder by 2019|magazine=Autosport|author=David Evans|accessdate=10 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== America's Cup ===\nPirelli is sponsor of [[Team New Zealand|Emirates Team New Zealand]] in the 35th [[America's Cup]] (2017).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/pirelli-boards-team-new-zealand|title=Pirelli boards Team New Zealand|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Winter Sports ===\nPirelli sponsors [[FIS Alpine World Ski Championships|Alpine World Ski Championship]] and [[Ice Hockey World Championships|Ice Hockey World Championship]] [[International Ice Hockey Federation|IIHF]] from 2017 to 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fis-ski.com/news-multimedia/news/article=pirelli-and-infront-seal-five-year-sponsorship-agreement-across-flagship-winter-sports-events.html|title=Pirelli and Infront seal five year sponsorship agreement across flagship winter sports events \u2013 FIS-SKI|website=FIS-SKI|language=en|access-date=2017-05-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171030215506/http://www.fis-ski.com/news-multimedia/news/article=pirelli-and-infront-seal-five-year-sponsorship-agreement-across-flagship-winter-sports-events.html|archive-date=30 October 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The company is also sponsor of the Italian Ski Team and of the Swiss Ski Team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://business.pirelli.com/global/en-ww/pirelli-sponsors-alpine-world-ski-championship-and-ice-hockey|title=Pirelli sponsors Alpine World Ski Championship and ice hockey from 2017 to 2021|website=business.pirelli.com|access-date=2017-05-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170614230543/http://business.pirelli.com/global/en-ww/pirelli-sponsors-alpine-world-ski-championship-and-ice-hockey|archive-date=14 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Motorsport==\nPirelli is the only allowed tyre brand in the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Motocyclisme|FIM]] [[World Superbike Championship]] since 2007 (along with its support classes, such as the [[Supersport World Championship]]).\nPirelli has also been awarded the contract for the control tyre supply in the [[British Superbike Championship]] from 2008 until at least 2010.<ref>[http://www.britishsuperbike.com/html/newsarticle.php?id=1203 British Superbikes 2007] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080320074840/http://www.britishsuperbike.com/html/newsarticle.php?id=1203 |date=20 March 2008 }}</ref>\nPirelli were also the official tyre supplier of the [[World Rally Championship]] from [[2008 World Rally Championship season|2008]] to [[2010 World Rally Championship season|2010]], until the company withdrew to focus on its Formula 1 commitments. Pirelli returned to the championship in [[2014 World Rally Championship season|2014]], however they only supply tyres for a few private teams as [[Michelin]] is the major tyre supplier. Pirelli was also supplied [[Grand-Am]] [[Rolex Sports Car Series]] from 2008 until at least 2010 before replaced by [[Continental AG]] in 2011. Pirelli is sponsor of rally and gymkhana driver [[Ken Block]]'s [[Hoonigan Racing Division]] since 2010.\n\nPirelli is the sole tyre supplier in [[Formula One]], following [[Bridgestone]]'s decision to withdraw from the role at the end of {{F1|2010}}.<ref>{{Cite news | title = Bridgestone to Cease Tire Supply to the FIA Formula One World Championship | url = http://bridgestone.com/corporate/news/2009110201.html | publisher = [[Bridgestone]] | date = 2 November 2009 | accessdate = 2 November 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20091104223536/http://bridgestone.com/corporate/news/2009110201.html | archivedate = 4 November 2009 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"WMSC230610\">{{cite web|title=World Motor Sport Council: 23 June 2010|url=http://www.fia.com/en-GB/mediacentre/pressreleases/wmsc/2010/Pages/wmsc_230610.aspx|work=fia.com|publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]|date=23 June 2010|accessdate=23 June 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626103652/http://www.fia.com/en-GB/mediacentre/pressreleases/wmsc/2010/Pages/wmsc_230610.aspx|archivedate=26 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Pirelli return to F1 after 20-year absence|url=http://www.f1fanatic.co.uk/2010/06/23/pirelli-return-to-f1-after-20-year-absence/|first=Keith|last=Collantine|work=F1 Fanatic|publisher=Keith Collantine|date=23 June 2010|accessdate=23 June 2010}}</ref> Pirelli previously competed in Formula One from {{F1|1950}}\u2013{{F1|1958}}, {{F1|1981}}\u2013{{F1|1986}} and {{F1|1989}}\u2013{{F1|1991}}. Pirelli has also supplied tyres for all [[FIA Formula 2 Championship]] and [[GP3 Series]] cars since 2011 and 2010 respectively.\n\nThe tyre manufacturer introduced a colour coding to recognize tyre compounds used by drivers during the racing weekend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.f1fanatic.co.uk/2011/03/18/pirelli-confirms-colours-tyres/|title=Pirelli confirms six different colours for tyres \u00b7 F1 Fanatic|date=2011-03-18|website=F1 Fanatic|access-date=2017-05-31}}</ref> For the benefit of the spectators at the track and the television audiences each compound has its own colour coding on the Pirelli and P Zero logos which appear on the sidewalls of the tyre. For the 2019 season, Pirelli reverted to using 3 colours to identify the dry weather tyres. However there still were 5 different compounds meaning that the same compound tyre can be represented by different colours throughout the season.\n\nPirelli were asked to design tyres that degraded rapidly in order to promote more pit stops and closer racing. At the end of the 2011 season, many F1 drivers praised Pirelli's comeback.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gpupdate.net/en/f1-news/271986/drivers-praise-pirelli-s-comeback-season/|title=Drivers praise Pirelli's comeback season|website=GPUpdate.net|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-06-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201131751/https://www.gpupdate.net/en/f1-news/271986/drivers-praise-pirelli-s-comeback-season/|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nControversy surrounded Pirelli's [[Formula 1 tyres]] as at the 2013 British Grand Prix seven Pirelli tyres failed: P\u00e9rez twice, Alonso, Hamilton, Gutierrez, Vergne, and Massa. Following a safety car period drivers were instructed to stay off the kerbs that were later found to be \"razor sharp\" and may have been the cause, but the president of the British Racing Drivers' Club rejected the idea that the kerbs could be at fault, saying that \"These kerbs have been in since 2009 and we have had thousands and thousands of cars go over these kerbs and they have been absolutely fine\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/23132957|title=BBC Sport \u2013 F1 boss Bernie Ecclestone dismisses talk of boycott|author=Andrew Benson|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> The incidents were described as \"unacceptable\" by F1 drivers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/23118249|title=BBC Sport \u2013 British GP: Lewis Hamilton says Pirelli tyre failures dangerous|author1=Lawrence Barretto  |author2=Andrew Benson |lastauthoramp=yes |work=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> It was later suggested that the cause of the tyre failures could be the teams putting them on the wrong side of the car. Pirelli stressed that the tyres are of an asymmetrical construction and are not interchangeable, and that if they are used correctly, they do not pose a threat to safety.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pirelli.com/tyre/ww/en/news/2013/07/02/pirelli-explanation-on-silverstone-facts-and-next-races/|title=Pirelli, explanation on Silverstone' facts and next races|work=pirelli.com|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> Pirelli changed the construction of the tyres to prevent further incidents, switching to kevlar belts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.f1fanatic.co.uk/2013/07/02/pirelli-to-use-prototype-tyres-for-german-grand-prix/|title=Kevlar belt tyres for Germany, new tyres for Hungary \u00b7 F1 Fanatic|date=2013-07-02|website=F1 Fanatic|access-date=2017-05-31}}</ref>\n\nDuring the second practice of the 2013 Belgian Grand Prix, two tyres failed: Vettel and Alonso. One senior figure at Pirelli described the failures as a \"big concern\", whilst Pirelli's motorsport director Paul Hembery admitted the tyre failures were \"a worry for the sport\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/23816972|title=BBC Sport \u2013 Belgian GP: Drivers demand reassurance Pirelli tyres are safe|author=Andrew Benson|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> Following these issues, just one day later [[Michelin]] announced that they could replace Pirelli as the tyre supplier for 2014. In October 2013 [[Fernando Alonso]] complained that \"the quality of the tyres is very on the limit\", and that they \"will not do 5km\". Pirelli motorsport director Paul Hembery said: \"Of course Alonso is one of the great F1 drivers, so to hear such comments is disappointing and below the standards you would expect from such a champion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/24409735|title=BBC Sport \u2013 Fernando Alonso criticises Pirelli tyres after Korean GP qualifying|author=Andrew Benson|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> In the Korean Grand Prix P\u00e9rez locked a front tyre heavily and then suffered a dramatic failure on the subsequent long straight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/24420547|title=BBC Sport \u2013 Korean GP: perfection from Vettel, less so from the tyres|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> Pirelli hit controversy at the Indian Grand Prix where they requested the teams run the tyres a limited number of laps due to their fragility. One senior engineer at a top team said this was the worst blistering ever experienced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/24690717|title=BBC Sport \u2013 Indian GP: Pirelli wants limited tyre running on safety grounds|author=Andrew Benson|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn pre-season testing for the 2014 season the tyre on Rosberg's car failed, sending Rosberg into a {{convert|200|mph|0|abbr=on}} spin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/25449812|title=BBC Sport \u2013 Nico Rosberg suffers tyre failure in Bahrain Pirelli test|author=Andrew Benson|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> The incident prompted considerable alarm, and Pirelli stated that the tyre \"will not be proposed again\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www1.skysports.com/f1/news/12472/9080138/pirelli-tyre-which-failed-on-rosbergs-car-was-prototype-that-wont-be-used-again |title=Pirelli: 'Prototype tyre which failed on Nico Rosberg's car won't be used again' | work=Sky Sports}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2014 Pirelli signed a contract with the FIA to supply tyres to Formula One for the 2014, 2015 and 2016 seasons.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/112150 |title=Pirelli concludes new Formula 1 tyre supply deal| work=Autosport | date=16 January 2014}}</ref> Later in 2014 [[Lewis Hamilton]] described the Pirelli wet weather tyres as \"They're not great tyres. That's no secret\".<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/29634110|title=BBC Sport \u2013 Lewis Hamilton & Sebastian Vettel call for better wet-weather tyres|author=Andrew Benson|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> \"These are comments by drivers that have not been made in an official way to us. Of course, if Pirelli was requested by the teams and the FIA to reconsider the technical capability of the wet tyre, Pirelli would do it immediately\" was the comment of Pirelli's motorsport director Paul Hembery.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAt the 2015 Belgian Grand Prix, during practice, Rosberg suffered a dangerous tyre delamination at {{convert|200|mph|0|abbr=on}}. Rosberg said the incident was \"quite a shock\".  During the subsequent drivers' briefing, double world champion Lewis Hamilton raised concerns about tyre safety following the high-speed blow-out suffered by teammate Nico Rosberg. Concerns were also brought up by four-time world champion Vettel, and double world champion Alonso. Pirelli relied on race director, Charlie Whiting, to defend Pirelli's record in the meeting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/34021994|title=Nico Rosberg tyre failure: Hamilton and Alonso raise concerns|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> During the race a tyre on Vettel's car suffered from a blowout at {{convert|200|mph|0|abbr=on}}. The four time world champion described the failure an \"unacceptable\", and added that Pirelli's tendency to blame failures either on debris on track or a driver going over a kerb for tyre failures was incorrect, confirming that \"I didn't go off the track and out of the blue the tyre explodes\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/34035036|title=Sebastian Vettel says Pirelli tyre failure unacceptable|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> Following the race Rosberg was critical of the poor quality of Pirelli tyres, saying \"Vettel exploding his tyre is really poor. It shouldn't happen and that it keeps on happening, in other categories as well and today with us, and with me on Friday both of us were just so lucky\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/f1/news/24182/9962863/vettel-launches-pirelli-attack|title=Sebastian Vettel & Nico Rosberg round on Pirelli after tyre blowouts|author=James Galloway|work=Sky Sports}}</ref> The [[Grand Prix Drivers' Association]] chairman said: \"We need to stop the sudden explosions.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/34063824|title=Belgian Grand Prix: Drivers demand end of blowouts|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> Immediately after the race Pirelli claimed that excessive wear caused the blowout, blaming Ferrari for running the tyre too long. However, following a more detailed analysis Pirelli said that in fact wear was not to blame, but instead a cut had caused the tyre failure.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/120596|title=Pirelli reveals F1 tyre investigation findings from Belgian GP|author=Ian Parkes|date=3 September 2015|work=AUTOSPORT.com}}</ref> To counteract further problems at the next Grand Prix, Monza, Pirelli wanted to insist that teams run the tyres at high pressure, beyond their design parameters. However, double world champion Lewis Hamilton described these rules as a \"disaster\" and double world champion Fernando Alonso described them as \"strange\" so Pirelli was forced to backtrack on their proposal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/34141910|title=Pirelli relaxes tyre limits after Lewis Hamilton & Alonso complaints|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> After these comments, Pirelli attempted to censor the drivers by asking them to not criticise the tyres in public in the future.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/34155703|title=Italian GP: Drivers told to keep worries over Pirelli tyres private|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe situation did not improve at the next Grand Prix at Monza. Here, Pirelli reported a higher than expected number of cuts forming in the tyres.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/120670|title=Italian GP: Pirelli reports high number of F1 tyre cuts at Monza|author1=Dieter Rencken  |author2=Lawrence Barretto |lastauthoramp=yes |date=6 September 2015|work=AUTOSPORT.com}}</ref> During the race, one of Hamilton's tyres dropped below the regulation pressure dictated by Pirelli, despite the tyre having been prepared by a Pirelli technician.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/formula1/32543096|title=Lewis Hamilton wins in Italy \u2013 reaction \u2013 BBC Sport|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> Neither Mercedes nor Hamilton were punished for the infringement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/34168014|title=Lewis Hamilton keeps Italian GP win after stewards' investigation|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> Later in 2016, the necessity to run Pirelli tyres at high pressure was described as a \"joke\" by triple world champion Lewis Hamilton, world champion Jenson Button, and world championship runner-up Felipe Massa.<ref>https://www.jamesallenonf1.com/2016/09/pirelli-starting-to-lower-minimum-f1-tyre-pressures-airs-concerns-over-2017-testing/</ref>\n\nAbove any criticisms, in 2016 the renewal of the contract as sole supplier was strongly supported by the protagonists of the Formula 1 circus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/formulaone/article-3173665/Christian-Horner-hopes-Pirelli-s-sole-tyre-F1-supplier-deal-extended-2016-despite-Michelin-interest.html|title=Horner hopes Pirelli's sole tyre F1 deal is extended beyond 2016|work=Mail Online|access-date=2017-05-31}}</ref>\n\nA number of changes to the [[Formula One|Formula 1]] tyres were introduced for the 2017 season. The most obvious visual difference was an increase of width by 25%, both front and rear, increasing from 245 to 305mm at the front and 325 to 405mm at the rear. The actual rim size remained unchanged from the traditional 13 inches.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/125375|title=Formula 1 2017 tyre rules: The key questions and Pirelli's plans|last=Parkes|first=Ian|work=Autosport.com|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThis is part of a package of measures expected to cut lap times by around five seconds relative to 2015: although the improvement might be even bigger.\n\nMost of that extra speed has been found through corners, as the cars have got wider and will generate at least 20% more downforce compared to last year thanks to bigger wings and increased aerodynamics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/38530543|title=2017 season: F1 looks back for its future with faster, wider cars|date=2017-01-09|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThese faster cornering speeds\u2014to the extent that some corners have now effectively become straights, already leading to circuit modifications\u2014have imposed significantly increased loads on the tyres, meaning that there is a completely new philosophy behind Pirelli\u2019s 2017 range. Having followed the brief to provide deliberate degradation for the past six seasons, there is now a new directive to make tyres with less degradation that are more resistant to overheating for the latest generation of much faster cars.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/127693|title=New Formula 1 tyres for 2017 have 'very low degradation'|last=Noble|first=Roberto Chinchero and Jonathan|work=Autosport.com|access-date=2017-05-31|language=en}}</ref> As a result, the tyre structure and compounds are brand new.\n\n==Overseas investment==\nIn April 2012, Pirelli & C. SpA signed joint venture agreement with [[Indonesia]]n counterpart PT Astra Autoparts a subsidiary of PT [[Astra International]] for the construction of a motorcycle tyre plant with a total investment of $120 million. 60 percent shares will be held by Pirelli. Pirelli hoped to strengthen its presence in the largest motorcycle market in the world, the [[Southeast Asia]] region which has 250 million motorcycles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/04/25/indonesia-welcomes-pirelli-italian-touch-local-shoes.html |title=Indonesia welcomes Pirelli, Italian touch for local shoes |date=25 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Audio system==\nIn July 2018, Pirelli launched a F1 wheel shaped Bluetooth speaker, P Zero Sound.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bruce |first1=Chris |title=Pirelli Design Launches Bluetooth Speaker That Looks Like F1 Wheel |url=https://www.motor1.com/news/258609/pirelli-design-tire-bluetooth-speaker/ |website=Motor1.com |accessdate=16 March 2020 |language=en |date=25 July 2018}}</ref> The Bluetooth speaker measures 12.9-inches in diameter, weighs 21 pounds and has a 100-watt amplifier, a 100mm midwoofer, a 25mm tweeter and also offers Bluetooth 4.0 with AptX for wireless connectivity. IXOOST<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ixoost.it/|title=IXOOST official site|access-date=2018-07-31}}</ref> is the manufacturer of P Zero Sound speaker, which majorly manufactures Motorsports-themed audio systems. The wheel shaped speaker costs \u20ac2400, which is equivalent to about $2,800.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Italy|Companies}}\n* [[List of Italian companies]]\n* [[Formula One tyres]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://www.pirellityre.com PirelliTyre.com] Pirelli Tyres Worldwide\n*[http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/41/41369.html Yahoo!] Pirelli & C. S.p.A. Company Profile\n{{Automotive industry in Italy}}\n{{Pirelli & C. SpA}}\n{{Rubber}}\n{{FTSE MIB companies}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Pirelli| ]]\n[[Category:Automotive companies of Italy]]\n[[Category:Tire manufacturers of Italy]]\n[[Category:Cycle parts manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1872]]\n[[Category:Rebreather makers]]\n[[Category:Italian brands]]\n[[Category:Watch manufacturing companies of Italy]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in Italy]]\n[[Category:1872 establishments in Italy]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Borsa Italiana]]\n", "name_user": "Jenniferjsale", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pirelli"}
{"title_page": "Ciucs\u00e2ngeorgiu", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Harghita\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Harghita County\n|official_name= Cs\u00edkszentgy\u00f6rgy\n|other_name=Cs\u00edkszentgy\u00f6rgy\n|image_shield=\n|image_skyline=Cs\u00edkszentgy\u00f6rgy.JPG\n|image_map=Ciucsangeorgiu jud Harghita.png\n|leader_name=J\u00f3zsef Gy\u00f6rgy\n|leader_party=UDMR\n|area_total_km2=240.72\n|coordinates             = {{coord|46|19|N|25|57|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code=537040\n|area_code=+40 266\n|website={{url|https://www.csikszentgyorgy.eu/}}\n}}\n\n''' Cs\u00edkszentgy\u00f6rgy''' ({{lang-hu|Cs\u00edkszentgy\u00f6rgy}} {{IPA-hu|\u02c8t\u0361\u0283i\u02d0ks\u025b\u0272\u025f\u00f8r\u025f|}}) is a commune in [[Harghita County]], [[Romania]]. It lies in the [[Sz\u00e9kely Land]], a ethnically Hungarian cultural region in eastern [[Transylvania]].\n\n==Component villages==\nThe commune is composed of nine villages:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible sortable\"\n!In [[Romanian language|Romanian]]!!In [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]\n|-\n|Arm\u0103\u0219eni||Cs\u00edkm\u00e9nas\u00e1g\n|-\n|Arm\u0103\u0219enii Noi||M\u00e9nas\u00e1g\u00fajfalu\n|-\n|Bancu||Cs\u00edkb\u00e1nkfalva\n|-\n|Ciob\u0103ni\u0219||Csob\u00e1nyos\n|-\n|Ciucs\u00e2ngeorgiu||Cs\u00edkszentgy\u00f6rgy\n|-\n|Cotormani||Kotorm\u00e1ny\n|-\n|Eghersec||Egersz\u00e9k\n|-\n|Ghiurche||Gy\u00fcrke\n|-\n|Potiond||Pottyond\n|}\n\n== History ==\nThe village formed part of the Sz\u00e9kely seat of [[Cs\u00edksz\u00e9k]], then from 1876 until 1918 to [[Cs\u00edk County]] in the [[Kingdom of Hungary]]. After the [[Treaty of Trianon]] of 1920, it became part of [[Romania]]. In 1940, the [[Second Vienna Award]] granted the [[Northern Transylvania]] to [[Hungary]] and the villages were held by Hungary until 1944. After Soviet occupation, the Romanian administration returned and the commune became officially part of Romania in 1947. Between 1952 and 1960, the commune fell within the [[Magyar Autonomous Region]], between 1960 and 1968 the Mure\u0219-Magyar Autonomous Region. In 1968, the province was abolished, and since then, the commune has been part of Harghita County.\n\n==Demographics==\nAt the 2011 census, the commune had a population of 4,839; out of them, 96% were [[Hungarians|Hungarian]], 1.3% were [[Romani people|Roma]] and 0.4% were [[Romanians|Romanian]].<ref>[http://www.recensamantromania.ro/rezultate-2/ Tab8. Popula\u0163ia stabil\u0103 dup\u0103 etnie \u2013 jude\u0163e, municipii, ora\u015fe, comune], 2011 census results, [[National Institute of Statistics (Romania)|Institutul Na\u021bional de Statistic\u0103]], accessed 20 February 2020.</ref> 94% of the commune population are [[Catholic Church in Romania|Roman Catholic]], 1.6% are [[Pentecostal Union of Romania|Pentecostal]], 0.5% are [[Reformed Church in Romania|Reformed]] and 0.4% are [[Romanian Orthodox Church|Orthodox]].<ref>[http://www.recensamantromania.ro/rezultate-2/ Tab13. Popula\u0163ia stabil\u0103 dup\u0103 religie \u2013 jude\u0163e, municipii, ora\u015fe, comune], 2011 census results, [[National Institute of Statistics (Romania)|Institutul Na\u021bional de Statistic\u0103]], accessed 20 February 2020.</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Cs\u00edkb\u00e1nkfalva.JPG|Bancu\nImage:Kotorm\u00e1ny.JPG|Cotormani\nImage:Josephinische Landaufnahme pg196.jpg|18th century map\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Communes of Harghita County}}\n{{1st Sz\u00e9kely Infantry Regiment}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ciucsangeorgiu}}\n[[Category:Communes in Harghita County]]\n[[Category:Sz\u00e9kely communities]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Harghita\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Harghita County\n|official_name=Ciucs\u00e2ngeorgiu\n|other_name=Cs\u00edkszentgy\u00f6rgy\n|image_shield=\n|image_skyline=Cs\u00edkszentgy\u00f6rgy.JPG\n|image_map=Ciucsangeorgiu jud Harghita.png\n|leader_name=J\u00f3zsef Gy\u00f6rgy\n|leader_party=UDMR\n|area_total_km2=240.72\n|coordinates             = {{coord|46|19|N|25|57|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code=537040\n|area_code=+40 266\n|website={{url|https://www.csikszentgyorgy.eu/}}\n}}\n\n'''Ciucs\u00e2ngeorgiu''' ({{lang-hu|Cs\u00edkszentgy\u00f6rgy}} {{IPA-hu|\u02c8t\u0361\u0283i\u02d0ks\u025b\u0272\u025f\u00f8r\u025f|}}) is a commune in [[Harghita County]], [[Romania]]. It lies in the [[Sz\u00e9kely Land]], an ethno-cultural region in eastern [[Transylvania]].\n\n==Component villages==\nThe commune is composed of nine villages:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible sortable\"\n!In [[Romanian language|Romanian]]!!In [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]\n|-\n|Arm\u0103\u0219eni||Cs\u00edkm\u00e9nas\u00e1g\n|-\n|Arm\u0103\u0219enii Noi||M\u00e9nas\u00e1g\u00fajfalu\n|-\n|Bancu||Cs\u00edkb\u00e1nkfalva\n|-\n|Ciob\u0103ni\u0219||Csob\u00e1nyos\n|-\n|Ciucs\u00e2ngeorgiu||Cs\u00edkszentgy\u00f6rgy\n|-\n|Cotormani||Kotorm\u00e1ny\n|-\n|Eghersec||Egersz\u00e9k\n|-\n|Ghiurche||Gy\u00fcrke\n|-\n|Potiond||Pottyond\n|}\n\n== History ==\nThe village formed part of the Sz\u00e9kely seat of [[Cs\u00edksz\u00e9k]], then from 1876 until 1918 to [[Cs\u00edk County]] in the [[Kingdom of Hungary]]. After the [[Treaty of Trianon]] of 1920, it became part of [[Romania]]. In 1940, the [[Second Vienna Award]] granted the [[Northern Transylvania]] to [[Hungary]] and the villages were held by Hungary until 1944. After Soviet occupation, the Romanian administration returned and the commune became officially part of Romania in 1947. Between 1952 and 1960, the commune fell within the [[Magyar Autonomous Region]], between 1960 and 1968 the Mure\u0219-Magyar Autonomous Region. In 1968, the province was abolished, and since then, the commune has been part of Harghita County.\n\n==Demographics==\nAt the 2011 census, the commune had a population of 4,839; out of them, 96% were [[Hungarians|Hungarian]], 1.3% were [[Romani people|Roma]] and 0.4% were [[Romanians|Romanian]].<ref>[http://www.recensamantromania.ro/rezultate-2/ Tab8. Popula\u0163ia stabil\u0103 dup\u0103 etnie \u2013 jude\u0163e, municipii, ora\u015fe, comune], 2011 census results, [[National Institute of Statistics (Romania)|Institutul Na\u021bional de Statistic\u0103]], accessed 20 February 2020.</ref> 94% of the commune population are [[Catholic Church in Romania|Roman Catholic]], 1.6% are [[Pentecostal Union of Romania|Pentecostal]], 0.5% are [[Reformed Church in Romania|Reformed]] and 0.4% are [[Romanian Orthodox Church|Orthodox]].<ref>[http://www.recensamantromania.ro/rezultate-2/ Tab13. Popula\u0163ia stabil\u0103 dup\u0103 religie \u2013 jude\u0163e, municipii, ora\u015fe, comune], 2011 census results, [[National Institute of Statistics (Romania)|Institutul Na\u021bional de Statistic\u0103]], accessed 20 February 2020.</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Cs\u00edkb\u00e1nkfalva.JPG|Bancu\nImage:Kotorm\u00e1ny.JPG|Cotormani\nImage:Josephinische Landaufnahme pg196.jpg|18th century map\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Communes of Harghita County}}\n{{1st Sz\u00e9kely Infantry Regiment}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ciucsangeorgiu}}\n[[Category:Communes in Harghita County]]\n[[Category:Sz\u00e9kely communities]]\n", "name_user": "2604:6000:ccc8:2800:4414:6452:37a3:6910", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ciucs%C3%A2ngeorgiu"}
{"title_page": "J\u00e4\u00e4karhu", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=ital}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image=Icebreaker J\u00e4\u00e4karhu.jpg\n| Ship caption=''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' arriving in Helsinki in April 1926.\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=\n| Ship country=Finland\n| Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Finland|state}}\n| Ship name=''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu''\n| Ship namesake=[[Finnish language|Finnish]] for \"[[polar bear]]\"\n| Ship owner=[[Finnish Board of Navigation]]<ref name=\"lloyds\" />\n| Ship operator=\n| Ship registry=[[Helsinki]], {{FIN}}<ref name=\"lloyds\" />\n| Ship ordered=17 April 1924\n| Ship builder=[[P. Smit Jr. Shipbuilding and Machine Factory]], [[Rotterdam]], Netherlands\n| Ship original cost=*[[Dutch guilder|\u0192]]1,563,000\n*([[Finnish markka|FIM]] 26,000,000)\n| Ship yard number=350<ref name=\"laurell140-151\">Laurell 1992, pp. 140\u2013151.</ref>\n| Ship laid down=\n| Ship launched=26 August 1925\n| Ship christened=\n| Ship completed=\n| Ship commissioned=2 March 1926\n| Ship decommissioned=24 February 1945\n| Ship in service=1926\u20131945\n| Ship identification=\n| Ship fate=Handed over to the Soviet Union\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=title\n| Ship country=Soviet Union\n| Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Soviet Union|naval}}\n| Ship name=''Sibiryakov'' (''\u0421\u0438\u0431\u0438\u0440\u044f\u043a\u043e\u0432'')\n| Ship namesake=[[Alexander Mikhaylovich Sibiryakov]]\n| Ship owner=\n| Ship operator=\n| Ship registry=\n| Ship awarded=\n| Ship commissioned=\n| Ship decommissioned=\n| Ship in service=1945\u20131972\n| Ship identification=\n| Ship fate=Broken up in 1972\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header=\n| Header caption=\n| Ship type=[[Icebreaker]]\n| Ship tonnage={{GRT|2,622}}<ref name=\"lloyds\">[[Lloyd's Register]] of Ships, [http://www.plimsollshipdata.org/pdffile.php?name=43a0302.pdf 1943\u20131944].</ref>\n| Ship displacement=4,836 tons\n| Ship length=*{{convert|78.45|m|ft|abbr=on}} ([[Length overall|overall]])\n*{{convert|75.00|m|ft|abbr=on}} ([[Waterline length|waterline]])\n| Ship beam=*{{convert|19.28|m|ft|abbr=on}} ([[moulded breadth|moulded]])\n*{{convert|18.50|m|ft|abbr=on}} (waterline)\n| Ship draught={{convert|6.5|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth=\n| Ship hold depth=\n| Ship decks=\n| Ship deck clearance=\n| Ship ramps=\n| Ship ice class=\n}}\n|-\n| Boilers:\n| Eight oil-fired boilers\n|-\n| Engines:\n| Three [[Marine steam engine#Triple or multiple expansion|triple-expansion steam engines]]<br />2&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;2,500&nbsp;[[indicated horsepower|ihp]] (stern); 2,600&nbsp;ihp (bow)\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header              = yes\n| Ship propulsion=Three propellers; two in stern and one in bow\n| Ship sail plan=\n| Ship speed={{convert|13.5|kn}} in open water\n| Ship range=\n| Ship endurance=\n| Ship crew=47\n| Ship time to activate=\n| Ship armament=Armed during the war\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu''''' was a [[Finland|Finnish]] and later [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[steamship|steam-powered]] [[icebreaker]]. Built in 1926 by [[P. Smit Jr. Shipbuilding and Machine Factory]] in [[Rotterdam]], Netherlands, she was the last and largest steam-powered state-owned icebreaker of Finland. After two decades of successful service, ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was handed over to the Soviet Union as [[Finnish war reparations to the Soviet Union|war reparation]] in 1945 and renamed '''''Sibiryakov'''''. She remained in service until the 1970s and was broken up in 1972.\n\n== Background and construction ==\n\n[[File:J\u00e4\u00e4karhu trials.jpg|thumb|left|''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' leaving for sea trials in Rotterdam.]]\n\nWhen the [[Treaty of Tartu (Russian\u2013Finnish)|Treaty of Tartu]] was signed on 14 October 1920, Finland agreed to return the Russian icebreakers that the [[White Guard (Finland)|Finnish White Guard]] had seized during the [[Finnish Civil War|Civil War]] in 1918. As a result, the largest and most powerful state-owned icebreaker of Finland at that time, [[Suur T\u00f5ll (icebreaker)|''W\u00e4in\u00e4m\u00f6inen'']], was handed over to Estonia in 1922. Since both the size of the ships calling at the Finnish winter ports and the amount of exported goods, especially forest products, had increased considerably since the [[First World War]], there was a definite need for a large and powerful icebreaker. One of the key issues was the beam of the existing icebreakers, {{convert|14|m|ft}}, which was not enough for the new ships used to transport goods across the Atlantic Ocean.<ref name=\"laurell133-139\">Laurell 1992, pp. 133\u2013139.</ref>\n\nIn 1923, the state allocated FIM 10 million for the design and development of a new icebreaker based on the experiences gained during the four years that ''W\u00e4in\u00e4m\u00f6inen'' had spent under the Finnish flag. The basic design of the new vessel, which was to have a beam of at least {{convert|18|m|ft}}, was awarded to experienced Finnish naval architects [[K. Albin Johansson]] and [[Ossian Tybeck]].<ref name=\"laurell140-151\" />\n\nBy June 1923, bids ranging from [[Finnish markka|FIM]] 20.2 to 35.5 million had been received from 24 shipyards representing eight nationalities. The most expensive offer was received from the Finnish [[Sandvikens Skeppsdocka och Mekaniska Verkstad|Sandvikens Skeppsdocka och Mekaniska Verkstads Ab]] that was already building another new icebreaker, [[Voima (1924 icebreaker)|''Voima'']], in Helsinki. In the end, the contract was awarded to the Dutch shipbuilder P. Smit Jr. Shipbuilding and Machine Factory from Rotterdam. The shipyard had recently constructed four ice-strengthened ships for the [[Finland Steamship Company]] and the technical director of the company had personally spent several weeks on board the Finnish icebreaker [[Sampo (1898 icebreaker)|''Sampo'']] during the past winter.<ref name=\"laurell140-151\" />\n\nThe contract for the construction of a new icebreaker was signed on 17 April 1924 after the Dutch government and the town council of Rotterdam agreed to subsidize the construction costs by 175,000 [[Dutch guilder]]s, bringing the final cost to \u01921,563,000 (FIM 26,000,000). She was launched on 26 August 1925<ref name=\"dutch_magazines\">Nieuwe Rotterdamsche Courant (26 August 1925 and 17 January 1926) and Het Centrum (24 December 1925). Excerpts available at [http://warshipsresearch.blogspot.com/2011/09/building-of-finnish-icebreaker-jaakarhu.html \"The building of the Finnish icebreaker J\u00e4\u00e4karhu according to the Dutch newspapers in 1925\u20131926\"], Warshipresearch, 10 September 2011.</ref> and given the name ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'', [[Finnish language|Finnish]] for [[polar bear]]. Curiously, her namesake animal is not a native species to Finland.<ref>[http://yle.fi/uutiset/polar_bear_cub_becomes_tourist_magnet/3343916 Polar bear cub becomes tourist magnet]. YLE, 19 March 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=21 May 2012}}</ref> As the new icebreaker was being built, Captain [[Johan Rosqvist]], who has previously commanded ''Sampo'', was selected as the first captain of the new icebreaker, and in the summer of 1925 he travelled to Rotterdam together with a chief engineer and a second engineer to supervise the construction and outfitting of his new ship.<ref name=\"laurell140-151\" />\n\nOn 13 January 1926 ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was ready for first sea trials in the [[North Sea]]. Although there were still issues with the oil-fired boilers by late February, it was agreed to take the delivery of the new icebreaker on 2 March 1926 and solve the problems later as the winter of 1926 had turned out to be very severe. Despite the best efforts of existing Finnish state-owned icebreakers, the ice conditions in the Gulf of Finland and the Sea of \u00c5land were extremely difficult and vast pack ice fields closed off the shipping lanes outside the island of [[Ut\u00f6, Finland|Ut\u00f6]] at the edge of the [[Archipelago Sea]].<ref name=\"laurell140-151\" /><ref name=\"ramsay321-324\" />\n\nAlthough sometimes called the largest and most powerful icebreaker in the world by the press in the 1920s, ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was no match for the Soviet polar icebreakers [[Icebreaker Yermak|''Yermak'']] and [[Krasin (1916 icebreaker)|''Svyatogor'']] that had nearly twice the displacement and over twice the power of the Finnish icebreaker. However, as a Baltic escort icebreaker she was considered better than the giants and was often compared with the Soviet icebreaker [[Lenin (1916 icebreaker)|''Lenin'']], which was roughly of the same size and was considered a very successful design.<ref name=\"ramsay321-324\">Ramsay 1949, p. 320\u2013324.</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Early career ===\n\n[[File:Jaakarhu 1920s.jpg|thumb|left|''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' in the port of [[Hanko]].]]\n\n''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' left Rotterdam on 3 March 1926. When the new icebreaker arrived in Finland on 7 March, she was welcomed by a number of icebound ships outside Ut\u00f6. After ''Sampo'' had arrived from [[Hanko]] with the Minister of Commerce and Industry, [[Tyko Reinikka]], other representatives of the state, and members of the press, the newest and largest state-owned icebreaker demonstrated her power by easily overcoming the notorious pack ice fields surrounding the island and escorting a convoy of three merchant ships to the open seas.<ref name=\"ramsay321-324\" /> After spending her first winter escorting ships in the Gulf of Finland, ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' arrived in Helsinki on 27 April 1926. In July she was drydocked in [[Liep\u0101ja]], Latvia, where her bottom was repainted.<ref name=\"laurell140-151\" />\n\nIn 1926, ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' became the first Finnish icebreaker to adopt Finnish as the command language. Since the officers and most of the crew spoke Swedish as their first language, this resulted in negative comments from the [[Swedish-speaking Finns|Swedish-speaking minority]], which considered Finnish to be \"the language of the peasants\", and even concerns about the safety of navigation. Captain [[Juho Lehtonen]], who had replaced Rosqvist in July 1926, even received [[hate mail]] from Swedish-speaking citizens, some of whom questioned his professional competence after a minor collision with a Swedish steamer [[SS Yrsa|''Yrsa'']] on 18 January 1927.<ref name=\"laurell163-167\">Laurell 1992, pp. 163\u2013167.</ref><ref>Kaukiainen 1992, p. 64.</ref>\n\n[[File:J\u00e4\u00e4karhu with other ships.jpg|thumb|right|''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' assisting icebound merchant ships in a Finnish port.]]\n\nWith the exception of the winter of 1929, the winters from 1927 until 1939 were relatively mild. Since ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was the most expensive to operate among the Finnish state-owned icebreakers, she saw little action during these years as she was always the last icebreaker to leave, beginning her season Helsinki and then moving to Hanko, and the first one to return.<ref name=\"kaukiainen114\">Kaukiainen 1992, p. 114.</ref> During very mild winters she was not put into service at all.<ref name=\"laurell140-151\" />\n\nHowever, the winter of 1929 was extremely difficult and by February the [[Baltic Sea]] was covered by ice all the way to the [[Danish straits]]. Finnish, Swedish and Soviet icebreakers were sent to escort merchant ships through the straits, and on 22 February 1929 ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was ordered to head south with a convoy of ships carrying export goods, assist and escort any icebound ship along the way and return with an inbound convoy to Turku and Hanko. She left on 24 February with a convoy of 12 ships and arrived at the edge of ice near [[Copenhagen]] on 4 March. After spending a few days assisting ships in the southern Baltic Sea, ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' began her journey home on 8 March and arrived in Hanko on 12 March. During the past 15 days she had, in addition to the ships in her own convoys, released and assisted 24 other ships and sailed {{convert|2140|nmi}}.<ref name=\"laurell176-184\">Laurell 1992, pp. 176\u2013184.</ref>\n\n=== Second World War ===\n\nWhen relations with the Soviet Union deteriorated in late 1939 and the [[Winter War]] began on 30 November 1939, the Finnish state-owned icebreakers were armed and assigned to a wartime icebreaker flotilla. ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was sent to the [[Gulf of Bothnia]] to escort ships across the [[Sea of \u00c5land]]. Although she was often attacked by Soviet bombers, the enemy never scored a direct hit on the icebreaker, giving her a reputation of a lucky ship among the Finnish seafarers. After the Winter War ended with the 1940 [[Moscow Peace Treaty]], ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' opened a channel to the icebound port of Hanko and helped to evacuate the city and the surrounding islands that had been leased to the Soviet Union as a naval base. During the period which later became known as the [[Interim Peace]], ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' resumed her peacetime duties as an escort icebreaker in the Gulf of Finland.<ref name=\"laurell272-274\">Laurell 1992, pp. 272\u2013274.</ref>\n\nWhen the [[Continuation War]] started in June 1941, the state-owned icebreakers were again called to arms. On 13 September 1941, icebreakers ''Tarmo'' and ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' participated in [[Operation Nordwind (1941)|Operation Nordwind]] together with Finnish and German naval ships.<ref name=\"laurell282-290\">Laurell 1992, pp. 282\u2013290</ref> The joint Finnish-German distraction manoeuvre was a complete failure. Not only did it fail to achieve its goal \u2013 it is uncertain if the Soviet forces even noticed the fleet \u2013 but when the ships turned back, [[Paravane (weapon)|paravanes]] dragged a Soviet naval mine against the hull of [[Finnish coastal defence ship Ilmarinen|Finnish coastal defence ship ''Ilmarinen'']], the flagship of the Finnish Navy, which sank in seven minutes following the explosion, claiming 271 lives.<ref>[http://koti.mbnet.fi/~karsikas/psl/ Panssarilaiva Ilmarisen tuho 13.9.1941]. {{retrieved |accessdate=24 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring the extremely difficult winter of 1942, ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was paired up with the [[diesel-electric transmission|diesel-electric]] [[Sisu (1938 icebreaker)|''Sisu'']]. On 2 February 1942, she ran aground while assisting an icebound convoy of six cargo ships, damaging her bow propeller. After returning from a dry dock in [[Stockholm]], Sweden, ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' resumed her duties in the Gulf of Finland, and together with ''Sisu'' she escorted almost 700 merchant ships through the ice-infested waters.<ref name=\"laurell282-290\" />\n\nThe winters of 1943 and 1944 were milder and ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'', being more expensive to operate than the smaller state-owned icebreakers, was not taken into service.<ref name=\"laurell282-290\" /> When the Continuation War ended with the signing of the [[Moscow Armistice]] on 19 September 1944, Finland was forced to hand over its best ice-strengthened tonnage to the Soviet Union as war reparations. This included the newest steam-powered icebreakers ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' and ''Voima''.<ref name=\"laurell292-294\" />\n\n=== Later Soviet service ===\n\n''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' and ''Voima'' were officially handed over to the Soviet Union as war reparations on 24 February 1945 after having been stationed in [[Leningrad]] since December 1944. ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was renamed ''Sibiryakov'' after [[Alexander Mikhaylovich Sibiryakov]], a Russian explorer of the Arctic regions, and [[Sibiryakov (1909 icebreaker)|another Russian icebreaker]] that had been sunk by the [[German cruiser Admiral Scheer|German cruiser ''Admiral Scheer'']] in August 1942.<ref name=\"laurell292-294\">Laurell 1992, pp. 292\u2013294</ref>\n\nDuring her time under the Soviet flag, ''Sibiryakov'' was a common sight in the [[Gulf of Finland]] and her familiar profile was easily recognized by the Finnish seafarers despite her Soviet colors and insignia. In the mid-1950s, she was sent to Rotterdam for modernization, which included installing two radar antennas and adding a new superstructure between the smoke stacks.<ref name=\"laurell292-294\" />\n\nBeing one of the last large steam-powered icebreakers in active service, ''Sibiryakov'' was used in a 1960s Soviet documentary film to represent the steam-powered icebreaker, ''Yermak'', which had been broken up in 1964.<ref name=\"laurell292-294\" /> She was also used in the 1969 Soviet/Italian film [[The Red Tent (film)|''The Red Tent'']] to represent another Soviet icebreaker, [[Krasin (1917 icebreaker)|''Krasin'']], which had participated in the rescue mission of [[Umberto Nobile]] and other survivors of the crash of [[Airship Italia|airship ''Italia'']] in 1928. While the original 1917-built icebreaker was still in service at that time, her extensive rebuilding in 1953\u20131960 had changed the look of the vessel completely and thus a more traditional-looking icebreaker was needed for the role.\n\n''Sibiryakov'' was retired after the winter of 1972 and sold for scrap. As the summer turned to autumn, she left the Baltic Sea for [[La Spezia]], Italy, arriving at the breakers on 16 October 1972.<ref name=\"laurell292-294\" />\n\n== Technical details ==\n\n[[File:J\u00e4\u00e4karhu propellers by P Smit.jpg|thumb|130px|left|Two of the three propellers installed on ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' used in an advertisement for the shipyard.]]\n\n''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was {{convert|78.5|m|ft}} [[overall length|long overall]] and {{convert|75|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[waterline length|at the waterline]]. Her hull had a moulded breadth of {{convert|19.28|m|ft}} and was {{convert|18.50|m|ft}} wide at the waterline. Her displacement was 4,836 tons at a draft of {{convert|6.5|m|ft}}. These main dimensions made ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' by far the largest icebreaker in service under the Finnish flag at that time \u2013 she was more than {{convert|10|m|ft}} longer and {{convert|4.5|m|ft}} wider than the second-largest icebreaker, ''Tarmo'', and had more than twice the displacement. Only the old ''W\u00e4in\u00e4m\u00f6inen'', handed over to Estonia in 1922, came close with an overall length of {{convert|75.4|m|ft}}, beam of {{convert|19.2|m|ft}} and displacement of 3,619 tons.<ref name=\"laurell344\">Laurell 1992, p. 344.</ref> Her bow, which had slightly rounder lines than the previous Finnish icebreakers,<ref name=\"ramsay315-324\">Ramsay 1949, pp. 315\u2013324.</ref> had a stem angle of 23\u201325 degrees and her hull, protected by an ice belt up to {{convert|28.6|mm|in}} thick, was divided into eight compartments by watertight transverse bulkheads. With a crew of 47, ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' had the largest crew among the Finnish steam-powered icebreakers even though she required less stokers than the older icebreakers due to her oil-fired boilers.<ref name=\"laurell140-151\" />\n\n''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was also the most powerful steam-powered icebreaker ever commissioned in Finland. Her three [[marine steam engine#Triple or multiple expansion|triple-expansion steam engines]], two with a [[maximum continuous rating]] of 2,500 [[indicated horsepower|ihp]] driving four-bladed nickel steel propellers weighing about 11 tons each<ref>[http://infocast.nl/storage/smit.jpg?__SQUARESPACE_CACHEVERSION=1289136972067 Advertisement for Machinefabriek & Scheepswerf van P. Smit Jr. N.V.]</ref> in the stern at 120 rpm, and one turning a third propeller of the same size in the bow at 130 rpm with a maximum continuous rating of 2,600 ihp. However, for short periods of time during icebreaking operations, the combined output of the engines could reach 9,200 ihp. Unlike the previous coal-burning icebreakers, ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' had eight oil-fired boilers with mechanical ventilation that consumed 2.5 to 4.5 tons of fuel oil per hour. Although she was the most expensive to operate, and for that reason she was always the last one to enter service and first one to sail back to her summer moorings, her endurance and range were considerably better than those of the older icebreakers since she could hold nearly 1,000 tons of fuel and required refueling only two or three times during normal winters.<ref name=\"laurell140-151\" /><ref name=\"laurell344\" />\n\nLike the old ''W\u00e4in\u00e4m\u00f6inen'', ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' had a heeling system with two pumps capable of transferring 650 tons of ballast water per hour between side tanks, heeling the vessel up to five degrees in ten minutes. In addition, she had six centrifugal pumps for moving 100 tons of water in five minutes between the fore and aft peak tanks to adjust her trim and release the icebreaker from compressive ice. For escort operations she had a towing winch and a stern notch that was considerably larger than in the older icebreakers.<ref name=\"laurell140-151\" /> Her single piece cast iron rudder weighed 9 tons.<ref name=\"dutch_magazines\" />\n{{Clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category|J\u00e4\u00e4karhu (ship, 1926)|''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu''}}\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{cite book |last= Kaukiainen |first= Yrj\u00f6 |title= Navigare Necesse \u2013 Merenkulkulaitos 1917\u20131992 |publisher= Gummerus Kirjapaino Oy | location = Jyv\u00e4skyl\u00e4 |year= 1992 |isbn= 978-951-47-6776-0}}\n*{{cite book |last= Laurell |first= Seppo |title= H\u00f6yrymurtajien aika |publisher= Gummerus Kirjapaino Oy | location = Jyv\u00e4skyl\u00e4 |year= 1992 |isbn= 978-951-47-6775-3}}\n*{{cite book |last= Ramsay |first= Henrik |title= J\u00e4\u00e4saarron murtajat |publisher=Werner S\u00f6derstr\u00f6m Osakeyhti\u00f6 (WSOY) | location = Helsinki |year= 1949 }}\n\n{{Icebreakers of Finland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jaakarhu (1925)}}\n[[Category:Icebreakers of Finland]]\n[[Category:1925 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Icebreakers of the Soviet Union]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=ital}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image=Icebreaker J\u00e4\u00e4karhu.jpg\n| Ship caption=''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' arriving in Helsinki in April 1926.\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=\n| Ship country=Finland\n| Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Finland|state}}\n| Ship name=''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu''\n| Ship namesake=[[Finnish language|Finnish]] for \"[[polar bear]]\"\n| Ship owner=[[Finnish Board of Navigation]]<ref name=\"lloyds\" />\n| Ship operator=\n| Ship registry=[[Helsinki]], {{FIN}}<ref name=\"lloyds\" />\n| Ship ordered=17 April 1924\n| Ship builder=[[P. Smit Jr. Shipbuilding and Machine Factory]], [[Rotterdam]], Netherlands\n| Ship original cost=*[[Dutch guilder|\u0192]]1,563,000\n*([[Finnish markka|FIM]] 26,000,000)\n| Ship yard number=350<ref name=\"laurell140-151\">Laurell 1992, pp. 140\u2013151.</ref>\n| Ship laid down=\n| Ship launched=26 August 1925\n| Ship christened=\n| Ship completed=\n| Ship commissioned=2 March 1926\n| Ship decommissioned=24 February 1945\n| Ship in service=1926\u20131945\n| Ship identification=\n| Ship fate=Handed over to the Soviet Union\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=title\n| Ship country=Soviet Union\n| Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Soviet Union|naval}}\n| Ship name=''Sibiryakov'' (''\u0421\u0438\u0431\u0438\u0440\u044f\u043a\u043e\u0432'')\n| Ship namesake=[[Alexander Mikhaylovich Sibiryakov]]\n| Ship owner=\n| Ship operator=\n| Ship registry=\n| Ship awarded=\n| Ship commissioned=\n| Ship decommissioned=\n| Ship in service=1945\u20131972\n| Ship identification=\n| Ship fate=Broken up in 1972\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header=\n| Header caption=\n| Ship type=[[Icebreaker]]\n| Ship tonnage={{GRT|2,622}}<ref name=\"lloyds\">[[Lloyd's Register]] of Ships, [http://www.plimsollshipdata.org/pdffile.php?name=43a0302.pdf 1943\u20131944].</ref>\n| Ship displacement=4,836 tons\n| Ship length=*{{convert|78.45|m|ft|abbr=on}} ([[Length overall|overall]])\n*{{convert|75.00|m|ft|abbr=on}} ([[Waterline length|waterline]])\n| Ship beam=*{{convert|19.28|m|ft|abbr=on}} ([[moulded breadth|moulded]])\n*{{convert|18.50|m|ft|abbr=on}} (waterline)\n| Ship draught={{convert|6.5|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth=\n| Ship hold depth=\n| Ship decks=\n| Ship deck clearance=\n| Ship ramps=\n| Ship ice class=\n}}\n|-\n| Boilers:\n| Eight oil-fired boilers\n|-\n| Engines:\n| Three [[Marine steam engine#Triple or multiple expansion|triple-expansion steam engines]]<br />2&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;2,500&nbsp;[[indicated horsepower|ihp]] (stern); 2,600&nbsp;ihp (bow)\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header              = yes\n| Ship propulsion=Three propellers; two in stern and one in bow\n| Ship sail plan=\n| Ship speed={{convert|13.5|kn}} in open water\n| Ship range=\n| Ship endurance=\n| Ship crew=47\n| Ship time to activate=\n| Ship armament=Armed during the war\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu''''' was a [[Finland|Finnish]] and later [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[steamship|steam-powered]] [[icebreaker]]. Built in 1926 by [[P. Smit Jr. Shipbuilding and Machine Factory]] in [[Rotterdam]], Netherlands, she was the last and largest steam-powered state-owned icebreaker of Finland. After two decades of successful service, ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was handed over to the Soviet Union as [[Finnish war reparations to the Soviet Union|war reparation]] in 1945 and renamed '''''Sibiryakov'''''. She remained in service until the 1970s and was broken up in 1972.\n\n== Background and construction ==\n\n[[File:J\u00e4\u00e4karhu trials.jpg|thumb|left|''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' leaving for sea trials in Rotterdam.]]\n\nWhen the [[Treaty of Tartu (Russian\u2013Finnish)|Treaty of Tartu]] was signed on 14 October 1920, Finland agreed to return the Russian icebreakers that the [[White Guard (Finland)|Finnish White Guard]] had seized during the [[Finnish Civil War|Civil War]] in 1918. As a result, the largest and most powerful state-owned icebreaker of Finland at that time, [[Suur T\u00f5ll (icebreaker)|''W\u00e4in\u00e4m\u00f6inen'']], was handed over to Estonia in 1922. Since both the size of the ships calling at the Finnish winter ports and the amount of exported goods, especially forest products, had increased considerably since the [[First World War]], there was a definite need for a large and powerful icebreaker. One of the key issues was the beam of the existing icebreakers, {{convert|14|m|ft}}, which was not enough for the new ships used to transport goods across the Atlantic Ocean.<ref name=\"laurell133-139\">Laurell 1992, pp. 133\u2013139.</ref>\n\nIn 1923, the state allocated FIM 10 million for the design and development of a new icebreaker based on the experiences gained during the four years that ''W\u00e4in\u00e4m\u00f6inen'' had spent under the Finnish flag. The basic design of the new vessel, which was to have a beam of at least {{convert|18|m|ft}}, was awarded to experienced Finnish naval architects [[K. Albin Johansson]] and [[Ossian Tybeck]].<ref name=\"laurell140-151\" />\n\nBy June 1923, bids ranging from [[Finnish markka|FIM]] 20.2 to 35.5 million had been received from 24 shipyards representing eight nationalities. The most expensive offer was received from the Finnish [[Sandvikens Skeppsdocka och Mekaniska Verkstad|Sandvikens Skeppsdocka och Mekaniska Verkstads Ab]] that was already building another new icebreaker, [[Voima (1924 icebreaker)|''Voima'']], in Helsinki. In the end, the contract was awarded to the Dutch shipbuilder P. Smit Jr. Shipbuilding and Machine Factory from Rotterdam. The shipyard had recently constructed four ice-strengthened ships for the [[Finland Steamship Company]] and the technical director of the company had personally spent several weeks on board the Finnish icebreaker [[Sampo (1898 icebreaker)|''Sampo'']] during the past winter.<ref name=\"laurell140-151\" />\n\nThe contract for the construction of a new icebreaker was signed on 17 April 1924 after the Dutch government and the town council of Rotterdam agreed to subsidize the construction costs by 175,000 [[Dutch guilder]]s, bringing the final cost to \u01921,563,000 (FIM 26,000,000). She was launched on 26 August 1925<ref name=\"dutch_magazines\">Nieuwe Rotterdamsche Courant (26 August 1925 and 17 January 1926) and Het Centrum (24 December 1925). Excerpts available at [http://warshipsresearch.blogspot.com/2011/09/building-of-finnish-icebreaker-jaakarhu.html \"The building of the Finnish icebreaker J\u00e4\u00e4karhu according to the Dutch newspapers in 1925\u20131926\"], Warshipresearch, 10 September 2011.</ref> and given the name ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'', [[Finnish language|Finnish]] for [[polar bear]]. Curiously, her namesake animal is not a native species to Finland.<ref>[http://yle.fi/uutiset/polar_bear_cub_becomes_tourist_magnet/3343916 Polar bear cub becomes tourist magnet]. YLE, 19 March 2012. {{retrieved|accessdate=21 May 2012}}</ref> As the new icebreaker was being built, Captain [[Johan Rosqvist]], who has previously commanded ''Sampo'', was selected as the first captain of the new icebreaker, and in the summer of 1925 he travelled to Rotterdam together with a chief engineer and a second engineer to supervise the construction and outfitting of his new ship.<ref name=\"laurell140-151\" />\n\nOn 13 January 1926 ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was ready for first sea trials in the [[North Sea]]. Although there were still issues with the oil-fired boilers by late February, it was agreed to take the delivery of the new icebreaker on 2 March 1926 and solve the problems later as the winter of 1926 had turned out to be very severe. Despite the best efforts of existing Finnish state-owned icebreakers, the ice conditions in the Gulf of Finland and the Sea of \u00c5land were extremely difficult and vast pack ice fields closed off the shipping lanes outside the island of [[Ut\u00f6, Finland|Ut\u00f6]] at the edge of the [[Archipelago Sea]].<ref name=\"laurell140-151\" /><ref name=\"ramsay321-324\" />\n\nAlthough sometimes called the largest and most powerful icebreaker in the world by the press in the 1920s, ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was no match for the Soviet polar icebreakers [[Icebreaker Yermak|''Yermak'']] and [[Krasin (1916 icebreaker)|''Svyatogor'']] that had nearly twice the displacement and over twice the power of the Finnish icebreaker. However, as a Baltic escort icebreaker she was considered better than the giants and was often compared with the Soviet icebreaker [[Lenin (1916 icebreaker)|''Lenin'']], which was roughly of the same size and was considered a very successful design.<ref name=\"ramsay321-324\">Ramsay 1949, p. 320\u2013324.</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Early career ===\n\n[[File:Jaakarhu 1920s.jpg|thumb|left|''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' in the port of [[Hanko]].]]\n\n''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' left Rotterdam on 3 March 1926. When the new icebreaker arrived in Finland on 7 March, she was welcomed by a number of icebound ships outside Ut\u00f6. After ''Sampo'' had arrived from [[Hanko]] with the Minister of Commerce and Industry, [[Tyko Reinikka]], other representatives of the state, and members of the press, the newest and largest state-owned icebreaker demonstrated her power by easily overcoming the notorious pack ice fields surrounding the island and escorting a convoy of three merchant ships to the open seas.<ref name=\"ramsay321-324\" /> After spending her first winter escorting ships in the Gulf of Finland, ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' arrived in Helsinki on 27 April 1926. In July she was drydocked in [[Liep\u0101ja]], Latvia, where her bottom was repainted.<ref name=\"laurell140-151\" />\n\nIn 1926, ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' became the first Finnish icebreaker to adopt Finnish as the command language. Since the officers and most of the crew spoke Swedish as their first language, this resulted in negative comments from the [[Swedish-speaking Finns|Swedish-speaking minority]], which considered Finnish to be \"the language of the peasants\", and even concerns about the safety of navigation. Captain [[Juho Lehtonen]], who had replaced Rosqvist in July 1926, even received [[hate mail]] from Swedish-speaking citizens, some of whom questioned his professional competence after a minor collision with a Swedish steamer [[SS Yrsa|''Yrsa'']] on 18 January 1927.<ref name=\"laurell163-167\">Laurell 1992, pp. 163\u2013167.</ref><ref>Kaukiainen 1992, p. 64.</ref>\n\n[[File:J\u00e4\u00e4karhu with other ships.jpg|thumb|right|''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' assisting icebound merchant ships in a Finnish port.]]\n\nWith the exception of the winter of 1929, the winters from 1927 until 1939 were relatively mild. Since ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was the most expensive to operate among the Finnish state-owned icebreakers, she saw little action during these years as she was always the last icebreaker to leave, beginning her season Helsinki and then moving to Hanko, and the first one to return.<ref name=\"kaukiainen114\">Kaukiainen 1992, p. 114.</ref> During very mild winters she was not put into service at all.<ref name=\"laurell140-151\" />\n\nHowever, the winter of 1929 was extremely difficult and by February the [[Baltic Sea]] was covered by ice all the way to the [[Danish straits]]. Finnish, Swedish and Soviet icebreakers were sent to escort merchant ships through the straits, and on 22 February 1929 ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was ordered to head south with a convoy of ships carrying export goods, assist and escort any icebound ship along the way and return with an inbound convoy to Turku and Hanko. She left on 24 February with a convoy of 12 ships and arrived at the edge of ice near [[Copenhagen]] on 4 March. After spending a few days assisting ships in the southern Baltic Sea, ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' began her journey home on 8 March and arrived in Hanko on 12 March. During the past 15 days she had, in addition to the ships in her own convoys, released and assisted 24 other ships and sailed {{convert|2140|nmi}}.<ref name=\"laurell176-184\">Laurell 1992, pp. 176\u2013184.</ref>\n\n=== Second World War ===\n\nWhen relations with the Soviet Union deteriorated in late 1939 and the [[Winter War]] began on 30 November 1939, the Finnish state-owned icebreakers were armed and assigned to a wartime icebreaker flotilla. ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was sent to the [[Gulf of Bothnia]] to escort ships across the [[Sea of \u00c5land]]. Although she was often attacked by Soviet bombers, the enemy never scored a direct hit on the icebreaker, giving her a reputation of a lucky ship among the Finnish seafarers. After the Winter War ended with the 1940 [[Moscow Peace Treaty]], ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' opened a channel to the icebound port of Hanko and helped to evacuate the city and the surrounding islands that had been leased to the Soviet Union as a naval base. During the period which later became known as the [[Interim Peace]], ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' resumed her peacetime duties as an escort icebreaker in the Gulf of Finland.<ref name=\"laurell272-274\">Laurell 1992, pp. 272\u2013274.</ref>\n\nWhen the [[Continuation War]] started in June 1941, the state-owned icebreakers were again called to arms. On 13 September 1941, icebreakers ''Tarmo'' and ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' participated in [[Operation Nordwind (1941)|Operation Nordwind]] together with Finnish and German naval ships.<ref name=\"laurell282-290\">Laurell 1992, pp. 282\u2013290</ref> The joint Finnish-German distraction manoeuvre was a complete failure. Not only did it fail to achieve its goal \u2013 it is uncertain if the Soviet forces even noticed the fleet \u2013 but when the ships turned back, [[Paravane (weapon)|paravanes]] dragged a Soviet naval mine against the hull of [[Finnish coastal defence ship Ilmarinen|Finnish coastal defence ship ''Ilmarinen'']], the flagship of the Finnish Navy, which sank in seven minutes following the explosion, claiming 271 lives.<ref>[http://koti.mbnet.fi/~karsikas/psl/ Panssarilaiva Ilmarisen tuho 13.9.1941]. {{retrieved |accessdate=24 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring the extremely difficult winter of 1942, ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was paired up with the [[diesel-electric transmission|diesel-electric]] [[Sisu (1938 icebreaker)|''Sisu'']]. On 2 February 1942, she ran aground while assisting an icebound convoy of six cargo ships, damaging her bow propeller. After returning from a dry dock in [[Stockholm]], Sweden, ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' resumed her duties in the Gulf of Finland, and together with ''Sisu'' she escorted almost 700 merchant ships through the ice-infested waters.<ref name=\"laurell282-290\" />\n\nThe winters of 1943 and 1944 were milder and ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'', being more expensive to operate than the smaller state-owned icebreakers, was not taken into service.<ref name=\"laurell282-290\" /> When the Continuation War ended with the signing of the [[Moscow Armistice]] on 19 September 1944, Finland was forced to hand over its best ice-strengthened tonnage to the Soviet Union as war reparations. This included the newest steam-powered icebreakers ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' and ''Voima''.<ref name=\"laurell292-294\" />\n\n=== Later Soviet service ===\n\n''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' and ''Voima'' were officially handed over to the Soviet Union as war reparations on 24 February 1945 after having been stationed in [[Leningrad]] since December 1944. ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was renamed ''Sibiryakov'' after [[Alexander Mikhaylovich Sibiryakov]], a Russian explorer of the Arctic regions, and [[Sibiryakov (1909 icebreaker)|another Russian icebreaker]] that had been sunk by the [[German cruiser Admiral Scheer|German cruiser ''Admiral Scheer'']] in August 1942.<ref name=\"laurell292-294\">Laurell 1992, pp. 292\u2013294</ref>\n\nDuring her time under the Soviet flag, ''Sibiryakov'' was a common sight in the [[Gulf of Finland]] and her familiar profile was easily recognized by the Finnish seafarers despite her Soviet colors and insignia. In the mid-1950s, she was sent to Rotterdam for modernization, which included installing two radar antennas and adding a new superstructure between the smoke stacks.<ref name=\"laurell292-294\" />\n\nBeing one of the last large steam-powered icebreakers in active service, ''Sibiryakov'' was used in a 1960s Soviet documentary film to represent the steam-powered icebreaker, ''Yermak'', which had been broken up in 1964.<ref name=\"laurell292-294\" /> She was also used in the 1969 Soviet/Italian film [[The Red Tent (film)|''The Red Tent'']] to represent another Soviet icebreaker, [[Krasin (1917 icebreaker)|''Krasin'']], which had participated in the rescue mission of [[Umberto Nobile]] and other survivors of the crash of [[Airship Italia|airship ''Italia'']] in 1928. While the original 1917-built icebreaker was still in service at that time, her extensive rebuilding in 1953\u20131960 had changed the look of the vessel completely and thus a more traditional-looking icebreaker was needed for the role.\n\n''Sibiryakov'' was retired after the winter of 1972 and sold for scrap. As the summer turned to autumn, she left the Baltic Sea for [[La Spezia]], Italy, arriving at the breakers on 16 October 1972.<ref name=\"laurell292-294\" />\n\n== Technical details ==\n\n[[File:J\u00e4\u00e4karhu propellers by P Smit.jpg|thumb|130px|left|Two of the three propellers installed on ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' used in an advertisement for the shipyard.]]\n\n''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was {{convert|78.5|m|ft}} [[overall length|long overall]] and {{convert|75|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[waterline length|at the waterline]]. Her hull had a moulded breadth of {{convert|19.28|m|ft}} and was {{convert|18.50|m|ft}} wide at the waterline. Her displacement was 4,836 tons at a draft of {{convert|6.5|m|ft}}. These main dimensions made ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' by far the largest icebreaker in service under the Finnish flag at that time \u2013 she was more than {{convert|10|m|ft}} longer and {{convert|4.5|m|ft}} wider than the second-largest icebreaker, ''Tarmo'', and had more than twice the displacement. Only the old ''W\u00e4in\u00e4m\u00f6inen'', handed over to Estonia in 1922, came close with an overall length of {{convert|75.4|m|ft}}, beam of {{convert|19.2|m|ft}} and displacement of 3,619 tons.<ref name=\"laurell344\">Laurell 1992, p. 344.</ref> Her bow, which had slightly rounder lines than the previous Finnish icebreakers,<ref name=\"ramsay315-324\">Ramsay 1949, pp. 315\u2013324.</ref> had a stem angle of 23\u201325 degrees and her hull, protected by an ice belt up to {{convert|28.6|mm|in}} thick, was divided into eight compartments by watertight transverse bulkheads. With a crew of 47, ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' had the largest crew among the Finnish steam-powered icebreakers even though she required less stokers than the older icebreakers due to her oil-fired boilers.<ref name=\"laurell140-151\" />\n\n''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' was also the most powerful steam-powered icebreaker ever commissioned in Finland. Her three [[marine steam engine#Triple or multiple expansion|triple-expansion steam engines]], two with a [[maximum continuous rating]] of 2,500 [[indicated horsepower|ihp]] driving four-bladed nickel steel propellers weighing about 11 tons each<ref>[http://infocast.nl/storage/smit.jpg?__SQUARESPACE_CACHEVERSION=1289136972067 Advertisement for Machinefabriek & Scheepswerf van P. Smit Jr. N.V.]</ref> in the stern at 120 rpm, and one turning a third propeller of the same size in the bow at 130 rpm with a maximum continuous rating of 2,600 ihp. However, for short periods of time during icebreaking operations, the combined output of the engines could reach 9,200 ihp. Unlike the previous coal-burning icebreakers, ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' had eight oil-fired boilers with mechanical ventilation that consumed 2.5 to 4.5 tons of fuel oil per hour. Although she was the most expensive to operate, and for that reason she was always the last one to enter service and first one to sail back to her summer moorings, her endurance and range were considerably better than those of the older icebreakers since she could hold nearly 1,000 tons of fuel and required refueling only two or three times during normal winters.<ref name=\"laurell140-151\" /><ref name=\"laurell344\" />\n\nLike the old ''W\u00e4in\u00e4m\u00f6inen'', ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu'' had a heeling system with two pumps capable of transferring 650 tons of ballast water per hour between side tanks, heeling the vessel up to five degrees in ten minutes. In addition, she had six centrifugal pumps for moving 100 tons of water in five minutes between the fore and aft peak tanks to adjust her trim and release the icebreaker from compressive ice. For escort operations she had a towing winch and a stern notch that was considerably larger than in the older icebreakers.<ref name=\"laurell140-151\" /> Her single piece cast iron rudder weighed 9 tons.<ref name=\"dutch_magazines\" />\n{{Clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Commons category|J\u00e4\u00e4karhu (ship, 1926)|Finnish icebreaker ''J\u00e4\u00e4karhu''}}\n*{{cite book |last= Kaukiainen |first= Yrj\u00f6 |title= Navigare Necesse \u2013 Merenkulkulaitos 1917\u20131992 |publisher= Gummerus Kirjapaino Oy | location = Jyv\u00e4skyl\u00e4 |year= 1992 |isbn= 978-951-47-6776-0}}\n*{{cite book |last= Laurell |first= Seppo |title= H\u00f6yrymurtajien aika |publisher= Gummerus Kirjapaino Oy | location = Jyv\u00e4skyl\u00e4 |year= 1992 |isbn= 978-951-47-6775-3}}\n*{{cite book |last= Ramsay |first= Henrik |title= J\u00e4\u00e4saarron murtajat |publisher=Werner S\u00f6derstr\u00f6m Osakeyhti\u00f6 (WSOY) | location = Helsinki |year= 1949 }}\n\n{{Icebreakers of Finland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jaakarhu (1925)}}\n[[Category:Icebreakers of Finland]]\n[[Category:1925 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Icebreakers of the Soviet Union]]\n", "name_user": "Tupsumato", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J%C3%A4%C3%A4karhu"}
{"title_page": "Dominic Pagon", "text_new": "{{Infobox tennis biography\n | name = Dominic Pagon\n | image = Dominic Pagon Jamaica Davis Cup Backhand 2016.jpg\n | caption = Dominic Pagon, Team Jamaica\n | country = {{flagicon|JAM}} [[Jamaica]]\n | residence = [[Kingston, Jamaica]]\n | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1988|3|08}}\n | birth_place = [[Kingston, Jamaica|Kingston]], Jamaica\n | death_date = \n | death_place =\n | height = {{height|m=1.75}}\n | turnedpro = 2008\n | plays = Left-handed \n | singlesrecord = 6-12\n | doublesrecord = 12-8}}\n\n'''Dominic Pagon''' (born March 8, 1988) is a professional [[tennis player]].<ref>http://www.itftennis.com/ProCircuit/players/player/profile.aspx?PlayerID=100029752</ref>\n\n== Playing career ==\n\nPagon has an [[International Tennis Federation]] win\u2013loss record of 21\u201328 primarily through his [[Davis Cup]] exploits. He has represented Jamaica in the Davis Cup on seven occasions and was nominated as the country\u2019s No. 1 player in 2008, 2009, 2013, 2014 and 2016. He has been selected to be the Captain for the Jamaican Davis Cup Team on four occasions (2013, 2016,2018 & 2019) and has 18 wins overall. In June 2019, Pagon broke the record for most doubles wins in the history of Jamaica's Davis Cup tennis with 12 wins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daviscup.com/en/players/player.aspx?id=800237072|title=Davis Cup - Players|work=daviscup.com|accessdate=3 September 2019}}</ref> He has played two [[ATP International Series]] singles event, both at the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame Champions Cup]] in 2007 & 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stevegtennis.com/draw-results/atp/Newport/2008/#to_sq|title=ATP Newport Draw 2008 - Men's Qualifying & Main Event Results|work=stevegtennis.com|accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref> Pagon represented Jamaica at the [[2006 Central American and Caribbean Games]] , [[2007 Pan American Games]] and was a doubles quarter finalist at the [[2014 Central American and Caribbean Games]] in Mexico. He was the top-ranked junior player in the Caribbean and Central American region as well as his home country. Pagon achieved a career-best [[ITF Junior Circuit]] ranking of No. 125. Pagon went to [[The College of William & Mary]] and earned All-Colonial Athletic Association honors three times as a Tribe player. He was named team captain in 2008 and won 55 singles / 47 doubles matches for W&M.<ref name=\"tribeathletics1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tribeathletics.com/coaches.aspx?rc=653&path=mten |title=William & Mary Athletics - 2016-17 Men's Tennis Coaching Staff |publisher=Tribeathletics.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Davis Cup==\n\n===Participations: (18\u201320)===\n\n{|\n|-valign=top\n|\n{|class=wikitable\n!Group membership\n|-bgcolor=#FFFFCC\n|World Group (0\u20130)\n|- style=\"background:#B0E0E6;\"\n|WG Play-off (0\u20130)\n|-bgcolor=#CCFFCC\n|Group I (0\u20130)\n|-bgcolor=#FFCCFF\n|Group II (0\u20132)\n|-bgcolor=#99CCFF\n|Group III (15\u201316)\n|-bgcolor=#FFCC99\n|Group IV (0\u20130)\n|}\n|\n{|class=wikitable\n!Matches by surface\n|-\n|Hard (14\u201317)\n|-\n|Clay (4\u20133)\n|-\n|Grass (0\u20130)\n|-\n|Carpet (0\u20130)\n|}\n|\n{|class=wikitable \n|-\n!Matches by type\n|-\n|Singles (6\u201312)\n|-\n|Doubles (12\u20138)\n|}\n|}\n* <small>{{increase}} {{decrease}} indicates the outcome of the Davis Cup match followed by [[Davis Cup#Ties and rubbers|the score]], date, place of event, [[Davis Cup structure|the zonal classification and its phase]], and [[Tennis court#Types of tennis courts|the court surface]].</small>\n\n{|class=wikitable\n!Rubber outcome\n!No.\n!Rubber\n!Match type (partner if any)\n!Opponent nation\n!Opponent player(s)\n!Score\n|-\n!colspan=7|{{increase}}3-0; [[2008 Davis Cup Americas Zone |16-20 July 2008]]; Country Club, [[Tegucigalpa]], Honduras; Americas Round Robin; Hard surface\n|-bgcolor=#99CCFF\n|bgcolor=98FB98|Victory\n|1\n|II\n|Singles\n|{{flagicon|HON}} [[Honduras Davis Cup team|Honduras]]\n|[[Keny 