wlson]]\n|1-6,2-6\n|-\n!colspan=7|{{increase}}3-0; [[2016 Davis Cup Americas Zone Group III|11 July 2016]]; Club de Tenis La Paz, [[La Paz]], Bolivia; Americas Round Robin; Clay surface\n|-bgcolor=#99CCFF \n|bgcolor=98FB98|Victory\n|31\n|III\n|Doubles (with [[Rowland Phillips (tennis)]])\n|{{flagicon|CUB}} [[Cuba Davis Cup team|Cuba]]\n|[[Cristian Rodriguez(tennis)]] / [[Osmel Rivera Granja]]\n|2-6,6-3,6-2\n|-\n!colspan=7|{{increase}}3-0; [[2016 Davis Cup Americas Zone Group III|11 July 2016]]; Club de Tenis La Paz, [[La Paz]], Bolivia; Americas Round Robin; Clay surface\n|-bgcolor=#99CCFF \n|bgcolor=98FB98|Victory\n|32\n|III\n|Doubles (with [[Rowland Phillips (tennis)]])\n|{{flagicon|PAN}} [[Panama Davis Cup team|Panama]]\n|[[Brendan Cockburn]] / [[Alejandro Benitez]]\n|6-0,6-1\n|-\n!colspan=7|{{decrease}}0-3; [[2016 Davis Cup Americas Zone Group III|11 July 2016]]; Club de Tenis La Paz, [[La Paz]], Bolivia; Americas Round Robin; Clay surface\n|-bgcolor=#99CCFF \n|bgcolor=FFA07A|Defeat\n|33\n|III\n|Doubles (with [[Rowland Phillips (tennis)]])\n|{{flagicon|BOL}} [[Bolivia Davis Cup team|Bolivia]]\n|[[Alejandro Mendoza (tennis)]] / [[Rodrigo Banzer]]\n|4-6,6-7\n|-\n!colspan=7|{{increase}}2-1; [[2019 Davis Cup Americas Zone Group III|17 June 2019]]; Costa Rica Country Club, [[Escazu]], Costa Rica; Americas Round Robin; Hard surface\n|-bgcolor=#99CCFF \n|bgcolor=98FB98|Victory\n|34\n|III\n|Doubles (with [[Rowland Phillips (tennis)]])\n|{{flagicon|PAN}} [[Panama Davis Cup team|Panama]]\n|[[Jorge Daniel Chevez]] / [[Luis Gomez (tennis) ]]\n|6-2,6-1\n|-\n!colspan=7|{{increase}}2-1; [[2019 Davis Cup Americas Zone Group III|17 June 2019]]; Costa Rica Country Club, [[Escazu]], Costa Rica; Americas Round Robin; Hard surface\n|-bgcolor=#99CCFF \n|bgcolor=98FB98|Victory\n|35\n|III\n|Doubles (with [[Rowland Phillips (tennis)]])\n|{{flagicon|TTO}} [[Trinidad & Tobago Davis Cup team|Trinidad & Tobago]\n|[[Akiel Duke]] / [[Nabeel Majeed Mohammed]]\n|6-3,7-6\n|-\n!colspan=7|{{increase}}2-1; [[2019 Davis Cup Americas Zone Group III|17 June 2019]]; Costa Rica Country Club, [[Escazu]], Costa Rica; Americas Round Robin; Hard surface\n|-bgcolor=#99CCFF \n|bgcolor=98FB98|Victory\n|35\n|III\n|Doubles (with [[Rowland Phillips (tennis)]])\n|{{flagicon|BER}} [[Bermuda Davis Cup Team|Bermuda]\n|[[Gavin Manders]] / [[Neal Towlson]]\n|6-1,6-3\n|-\n!colspan=7|{{increase}}2-1; [[2019 Davis Cup Americas Zone Group III|17 June 2019]]; Costa Rica Country Club, [[Escazu]], Costa Rica; Americas Round Robin; Hard surface\n|-bgcolor=#99CCFF \n|bgcolor=FFA07A|Defeat\n|36\n|III\n|Doubles (with [[Dimitri Bird]])\n|{{flagicon|CUB}} [[Cuba Davis Cup Team|Cuba]\n|[[Yoan Perez]] / [[Osmel Rivera Granja]]\n|6-4,7-6\n|-\n!colspan=7|{{increase}}2-1; [[2019 Davis Cup Americas Zone Group III|17 June 2019]]; Costa Rica Country Club, [[Escazu]], Costa Rica; Americas Round Robin; Hard surface\n|-bgcolor=#99CCFF \n|bgcolor=FFA07A|Defeat\n|37\n|III\n|Doubles (with [[Dimitri Bird]])\n|{{flagicon|HON}} [[Honduras Davis Cup Team|Honduras]\n|[[Keny Turcios]] / [[Gabriel Zuniga Mendoza]]\n|4-6,6-1,6-4\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nPagon was born in Kingston, Jamaica and started playing tennis at six years old. He was given the opportunity at age 14  to attend [[Saddlebrook Academies]], a tennis and golf academy in Tampa Florida. At the age of 17, Pagon was offered a scholarship to attend the College of William and Mary and graduated in 2009 with a degree in [[Economics]]. He is the son of Nigel Pagon and Shirley Wilson.<ref name=\"tribeathletics1\"/>\n\n==Coaching career==\nThe 2016-17 season will be his second season as an assistant to head coach Jeff Kader at his alma mater The College of William and Mary.\n\nIn their first year, they guided W&M to a 15-9 record and its first [[Intercollegiate Tennis Association]] ranking in five years and climbed as high as No. 60 in the nation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypress.com/dp-spt-star-track-pagon-20160803-story.html |title=Star Track: Dominic Pagon |publisher=Daily Press |date= |accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ITF}}\n*{{DavisCup player}}\n*{{ATP}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pagon, Dominic}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Jamaican male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Tennis players at the 2007 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games competitors for Jamaica]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox tennis biography\n | name = Dominic Pagon\n | image = Dominic Pagon Jamaica Davis Cup Backhand 2016.jpg\n | caption = Dominic Pagon, Team Jamaica\n | country = {{flagicon|JAM}} [[Jamaica]]\n | residence = [[Kingston, Jamaica]]\n | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1988|3|08}}\n | birth_place = [[Kingston, Jamaica|Kingston]], Jamaica\n | death_date = \n | death_place =\n | height = {{height|m=1.75}}\n | turnedpro = 2008\n | plays = Left-handed \n | singlesrecord = 6-12\n | doublesrecord = 12-8}}\n\n'''Dominic Pagon''' (born March 8, 1988) is a professional [[tennis player]].<ref>http://www.itftennis.com/ProCircuit/players/player/profile.aspx?PlayerID=100029752</ref>\n\n== Playing career ==\n\nPagon has an [[International Tennis Federation]] win\u2013loss record of 21\u201328 primarily through his [[Davis Cup]] exploits. He has represented Jamaica in the Davis Cup on seven occasions and was nominated as the country\u2019s No. 1 player in 2008, 2009, 2013, 2014 and 2016. He has been selected to be the Captain for the Jamaican Davis Cup Team on four occasions (2013, 2016,2018 & 2019) and has 18 wins overall. In June 2019, Pagon broke the record for most doubles wins in the history of Jamaica's Davis Cup tennis with 12 wins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daviscup.com/en/players/player.aspx?id=800237072|title=Davis Cup - Players|work=daviscup.com|accessdate=3 September 2019}}</ref> He has played two [[ATP International Series]] singles event, both at the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame Champions Cup]] in 2007 & 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stevegtennis.com/draw-results/atp/Newport/2008/#to_sq|title=ATP Newport Draw 2008 - Men's Qualifying & Main Event Results|work=stevegtennis.com|accessdate=18 April 2017}}</ref> Pagon represented Jamaica at the [[2006 Central American and Caribbean Games]] , [[2007 Pan American Games]] and was a doubles quarter finalist at the [[2014 Central American and Caribbean Games]] in Mexico. He was the top-ranked junior player in the Caribbean and Central American region as well as his home country. Pagon achieved a career-best [[ITF Junior Circuit]] ranking of No. 125. Pagon went to [[The College of William & Mary]] and earned All-Colonial Athletic Association honors three times as a Tribe player. He was named team captain in 2008 and won 55 singles / 47 doubles matches for W&M.<ref name=\"tribeathletics1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tribeathletics.com/coaches.aspx?rc=653&path=mten |title=William & Mary Athletics - 2016-17 Men's Tennis Coaching Staff |publisher=Tribeathletics.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Davis Cup==\n\n===Participations: (18\u201320)===\n\n{|\n|-valign=top\n|\n{|class=wikitable\n!Group membership\n|-bgcolor=#FFFFCC\n|World Group (0\u20130)\n|- style=\"background:#B0E0E6;\"\n|WG Play-off (0\u20130)\n|-bgcolor=#CCFFCC\n|Group I (0\u20130)\n|-bgcolor=#FFCCFF\n|Group II (0\u20132)\n|-bgcolor=#99CCFF\n|Group III (15\u201316)\n|-bgcolor=#FFCC99\n|Group IV (0\u20130)\n|}\n|\n{|class=wikitable\n!Matches by surface\n|-\n|Hard (14\u201317)\n|-\n|Clay (4\u20133)\n|-\n|Grass (0\u20130)\n|-\n|Carpet (0\u20130)\n|}\n|\n{|class=wikitable \n|-\n!Matches by type\n|-\n|Singles (6\u201312)\n|-\n|Doubles (12\u20138)\n|}\n|}\n* <small>{{increase}} {{decrease}} indicates the outcome of the Davis Cup match followed by [[Davis Cup#Ties and rubbers|the score]], date, place of event, [[Davis Cup structure|the zonal classification and its phase]], and [[Tennis court#Types of tennis courts|the court surface]].</small>\n\n{|class=wikitable\n!Rubber 